This introductory financial accounting course, part of the ACCA-X series on edX, covers fundamentals like double-entry bookkeeping, payroll, ledger accounts, and trial balance preparation. Designed for students and professionals, it builds practical skills in recording transactions and understanding accounting systems. The interactive course features expert instruction and offers a joint certificate upon completion.
This self-paced introductory financial accounting course, developed by ACCA-X and delivered via edX, provides foundational knowledge in accounting principles. It covers core topics including business transactions, double-entry bookkeeping, payroll, ledgers, and trial balance preparation. Designed for students and professionals, the course offers interactive content and leads to a joint certification from ACCA and XuetangX.
This self-paced introductory course covers core bookkeeping principles, including business transactions, double-entry systems, payroll, ledger accounts, and trial balance preparation. Designed for beginners, it serves as a foundation for careers in business, finance, or ACCA exam preparation (FA1), with no prior accounting knowledge required.
This intermediate financial accounting course, part of the ACCA-X series, teaches core principles like GAAP, double-entry bookkeeping, and preparing financial statements, including partnership accounts. Designed for learners with basic accounting knowledge, it features interactive content and expert instruction to build practical skills for real-world business scenarios.
This intermediate financial accounting course, offered via ACCA-X and edX, provides essential knowledge for aspiring accountants and business leaders. It covers core topics including accounting principles, double-entry bookkeeping, financial statement preparation, and partnership accounts. Designed with interactive learning activities, the course features expert instruction and leads to a joint certification from ACCA and XuetangX.
This intermediate-level bookkeeping course builds on foundational knowledge, focusing on applying core accounting principles to prepare financial statements and reconcile accounts. It equips learners with skills for roles like bookkeeper and prepares them for the ACCA FA2 exam, covering transaction recording and financial reporting essentials.
This introductory management accounting course, part of the ACCA-X series, provides foundational knowledge for aspiring business leaders and accountants. It focuses on transforming data into actionable information for planning and decision-making. Key topics include the purpose of cost accounting, cost classification, and spreadsheet applications. The interactive online course features expert instruction and offers a joint certificate upon completion.
This introductory management accounting course, designed by Epigeum (Imperial College London) and offered via ACCA-X on edX, provides foundational knowledge for aspiring accountants and business professionals. It covers core concepts like cost classification, data analysis for decision-making, and spreadsheet use. The 10-week Chinese-adapted program includes interactive activities and leads to a joint certification, serving as a gateway into the finance and accounting industry.
This self-paced introductory course covers core management accounting concepts, including cost classification, recording, and spreadsheet applications. Designed for beginners, it builds foundational knowledge for business, finance, or ACCA exam preparation, without requiring prior accounting experience.
This intermediate management accounting course, part of the ACCA-X series, equips learners with essential skills for business decision-making. It focuses on cost accounting, cash management, and cost-volume-profit analysis. Designed for those with foundational knowledge, the course features interactive content and expert instruction, culminating in a joint certification from ACCA and XuetangX.
This intermediate management accounting course, offered in self-paced mode, equips learners with essential skills for managerial decision-making. It covers cost accounting fundamentals, cash flow management, and cost-volume-profit analysis. Designed for those with basic accounting knowledge, the course features interactive content and leads to a joint certification from ACCA and XuetangX.
This intermediate-level course builds on foundational management accounting knowledge, focusing on costing techniques and using financial information for business decision-making. It prepares learners for professional accounting roles and related certification exams, enhancing skills in analyzing and applying management accounting principles.
This course explores winemaking from grape cultivation to bottling, covering viticulture and oenology principles. Learn to evaluate wine's sensory qualities, understand vineyard management, and compare winemaking techniques. It also addresses sustainability in the global wine industry, suitable for both beginners and enthusiasts.
This self-paced course provides a foundational understanding of human biology, focusing on cells and tissues. It covers the structure and function of the four primary tissue types—epithelial, connective, muscle, and nervous—in both health and disease. Designed to prepare learners for health sciences and careers, it uses engaging videos, animations, and quizzes to teach core concepts in anatomy and physiology.
This course explores entrepreneurial management through the metaphor of four seasons, integrating artistic thinking with technical execution. It covers lean startup, business model innovation, value creation, and sustainable growth, using 24 solar terms to address key entrepreneurial challenges. The curriculum emphasizes practical skills, innovation, and adaptability for navigating the entrepreneurial journey.
This online course systematically teaches modern Japanese grammar through 10 thematic units, progressing from basic to advanced levels. It focuses on practical communication skills, supplemented by cultural insights, usage analysis, and conversational practice. The course emphasizes functional grammar application without covering introductory writing or phonetic systems.
This course explores the identification and sustainable utilization of wild edible plants in China. It covers their nutritional, medicinal, and economic value, rooted in the traditional concept of "food as medicine." The curriculum systematically introduces various species, their biological traits, processing technologies, and comprehensive development for food, industry, and ecological purposes, while also incorporating cultural stories.
This course introduces the core principles of landscape architecture, covering its concepts, traditional and modern art forms, design processes, spatial composition, and its relationships with natural systems and human society. It provides essential theoretical foundations for advanced landscape planning and design studies.
This course introduces the fundamental principles of landscape architecture, covering its concepts, traditional and modern landscape art, design processes, spatial composition, and its relationships with natural systems and human society. It provides essential theoretical foundations for advanced landscape planning and design studies.
This introductory course on plant landscape planning and design covers core concepts, functions, historical features, design principles, spatial construction, and integration with other landscape elements. It includes specialized topics like flower displays and design standards, aiming to develop professional skills and industry insights for landscape architecture and urban planning students.
This course explores the integration of digital technology in fashion, covering computer-aided design, virtual garments, digital customization, functional textiles, 3D printing, big data applications, and digital cultural communication. It challenges traditional views and encourages rethinking the future of the fashion and textile industries.
This course explores the design journeys of 12 iconic fashion designers from Britain, France, and Italy, including pioneers like Chanel, Dior, and McQueen. It introduces key concepts in fashion design, runway shows, and design elements, blending professional knowledge with accessible English to provide a foundational understanding of the fashion industry.
This course introduces the core concepts of garment CAD, covering system configurations and current development trends globally. Through hands-on practice, students learn to utilize key functions of both 2D and 3D garment CAD software for practical application in fashion design.
This introductory C programming course covers fundamental concepts and techniques for problem-solving through structured code. It explores C's origins linked to UNIX development and emphasizes practical applications in computational thinking. The curriculum focuses on core programming principles, syntax, and algorithmic design using the C language.
This course covers advanced C programming, focusing on problem-solving and team-based software development. It explores C's historical significance in operating systems and emphasizes practical applications for computational challenges.
This course introduces software engineering fundamentals, focusing on requirements analysis and testing. It critically examines agile methods like Scrum and XP, covers object-oriented techniques and UML through a case study, and demonstrates automation tools to enhance development efficiency. Key themes include process improvement, quality assurance, and software reuse.
This course covers fundamental principles of vibrations, waves, and wave optics. Students will learn key concepts such as harmonic motion, wave superposition, interference, diffraction, and polarization. Emphasis is placed on applying theoretical knowledge to analyze real-world phenomena like double-slit interference and diffraction patterns. The module aims to develop practical problem-solving skills in physics.
This self-paced university physics course covers core principles of mechanics and thermodynamics, including fundamental laws, research methods, and applications in fields like aerospace and materials science. Students learn to analyze mechanical and thermal systems using calculus and vector operations, applying concepts such as energy conservation and entropy to solve real-world problems.
This course introduces modern physics, focusing on relativity and quantum mechanics. It covers special relativity principles, Lorentz transformations, and relativistic effects, along with quantum concepts like wave-particle duality and the Schrödinger equation. Designed to inspire innovative thinking, it explores foundational theories behind modern technologies.
This self-paced university physics course focuses on electromagnetism, covering the fundamental principles of electric and magnetic fields. Key topics include electrostatics, magnetostatics, and electromagnetic induction, explained through core laws such as Coulomb's Law, Gauss's Law, and Faraday's Law. Students learn to analyze and solve basic electromagnetic problems using these foundational theories.
This course explores technological innovation history since the 18th century, focusing on three industrial revolutions. It examines key figures, societal impacts, and underlying ideas driving innovation. The goal is to inspire reflection on past revolutions and foster discussion on the fourth industrial revolution's influence on humanity.
This course explores technological innovation history since the 18th century, focusing on three industrial revolutions. It examines key figures, societal impacts, and underlying ideas driving innovation. The course aims to inspire reflection on past revolutions and foster discussion about the Fourth Industrial Revolution's influence on humanity.
This course explores technological innovation history since the 18th century, covering key industrial revolutions and their transformations. It examines historical lessons, figures' stories, societal impacts, and underlying innovation philosophies. The course aims to inspire reflection on past revolutions and foster discussion on the Fourth Industrial Revolution's influence.
This graduate-level course on Advanced Database Systems covers core DBMS implementation techniques, including data organization, storage, retrieval, concurrency control, recovery, and distributed databases. It combines theory and practice to build a deep understanding of relational systems and develop problem-solving skills for modern data management challenges.
This foundational Management course (Spring 2019) systematically introduces core concepts, principles, and methods of management. It covers key areas like decision-making, organizational culture, and managing individuals, teams, and organizations. The course blends theory with practical application, emphasizing real-world scenarios and traditional Chinese insights. It aims to develop essential managerial skills and strategic thinking for future roles.
This course surveys ancient Western philosophy from 400 BC to medieval scholasticism, focusing on its historical development and logical interpretation. Assessment includes video lectures, two quizzes (60% of grade), and a final exam (40%). Passing requires 60/100 points, with 85 for excellence.
This online course, "Western Philosophy II: Modern Period," systematically explores key philosophical ideas with rigorous logic. It emphasizes critical thinking and intellectual engagement through abstract theories. Assessment includes chapter quizzes (20%), a midterm (20%), and a final exam (60%), requiring dedicated study for deeper understanding.
"General Chemistry" is a foundational course for first-year science students, covering atomic/molecular structures, chemical equilibria, thermodynamics, kinetics, and organic chemistry basics. It integrates applications in life, environmental, and materials sciences to illustrate chemistry's interdisciplinary relevance. The course aims to build a broad understanding of modern chemical principles and problem-solving skills. Assessment includes chapter tests (40%) and a final exam (60%).
This Microbiology course (Spring 2019) covers the fundamentals of microorganisms, including their morphology, physiology, genetics, ecology, and classification. It explores their roles in medicine, industry, agriculture, and the environment. The teaching method combines lectures, discussions, and multimedia to encourage critical thinking and self-directed learning. Assessment is based on chapter tests (60%) and a final exam (40%).
This course examines major environmental pollution incidents like the Songhua River and London Smog events through case studies. It analyzes causes, emergency responses, ecological impacts, and restoration measures. The curriculum also explores China's environmental emergency management system, covering its principles and frameworks. Teaching methods combine instructor-led discussions with problem-based learning to deepen understanding of emergency response mechanisms.
This course examines major environmental pollution incidents through case studies, including the Songhua River and London smog events. It analyzes causes, emergency responses, ecological impacts, and restoration measures. The curriculum also explores China's environmental emergency management framework, principles, and systems using interactive teaching methods to deepen understanding of crisis management protocols.
This mandatory graduate course on Research Ethics and Academic Norms (Spring 2019) cultivates students' awareness of fundamental ethical principles and academic integrity. It focuses on helping students avoid academic misconduct, enhance research standardization, and establish a solid foundation for rigorous scientific work.
This self-paced course introduces the principles of environmental geoscience, covering the composition and characteristics of Earth's environmental systems. It focuses on the migration, transformation, and spatiotemporal patterns of matter and energy. The course aims to build a foundational understanding for environmental science and engineering, develop integrated thinking and innovation skills, and promote harmonious, healthy living. Assessment is based entirely on regular coursework.
This course introduces the composition and characteristics of Earth's environmental systems, covering material and energy transfer processes along with their spatiotemporal variations. It equips students with fundamental geoscience methods for environmental investigation, fostering integrated thinking and innovation. Serving as a foundational geoscience component for environmental science and engineering, it supports research expansion and promotes sustainable living.
This course explores the research methodologies and scholarly journeys of five renowned Chinese historians: Chen Yuan, Bai Shouyi, Liu Naihe, He Ziquan, and Liu Jiahe. Through lectures by their academic successors, it examines their lives, key contributions, and distinct approaches to historical study. The course aims to impart their intellectual legacy and historiographical practices. Assessment is based on chapter quizzes after video lectures.
This course, "Restoration Ecology," covers core principles, techniques, and methods in ecological restoration, featuring the latest global advances and case studies. It utilizes multimedia tools like animations and videos for engaging instruction. Suitable for students and professionals in environmental, ecological, and related fields, the course is designed to impart up-to-date knowledge and practical skills in restoration ecology.
This course focuses on fat loss and body shaping through exercise, targeting individuals with sedentary lifestyles and slow metabolism. It covers tailored training plans for men and women, emphasizing muscle building to boost metabolism and burn calories efficiently. Practical workouts are combined with theoretical knowledge of muscle functions to prevent injuries and optimize results. Participants learn to design personalized fitness plans with appropriate weights, sets, and repetitions to achieve their goals effectively.
This course focuses on key joints like the neck, shoulders, spine, hips, knees, and ankles. It covers joint structure, function, and self-assessment methods. Students learn simple, scientific exercises to promote joint health, enabling them to integrate suitable activities into daily life for improved well-being.
This course explores how exercise aids in preventing and managing chronic diseases like obesity, cardiovascular issues, and osteoporosis. It covers causes, symptoms, and tailored physical activities to enhance health literacy and promote a healthy lifestyle.
This course addresses declining fitness among university students through video-based instruction. It covers physical activity concepts, monitoring methods, and training techniques for aerobic endurance, strength, and flexibility improvement. Practical evaluation approaches are integrated to enhance both theoretical knowledge and physical capabilities.
This course introduces 30 practical Chinese martial arts techniques across three modules: close combat, long-range combat, and self-defense applications. Students learn fundamental skills like kicking, striking, throwing, and grappling to enhance physical fitness, self-protection abilities, and risk awareness. It also explores the cultural heritage of martial arts, fostering both practical competence and traditional values.
This course introduces world classic dance appreciation, starting with Chinese traditional dance. It covers cultural backgrounds, performance styles, and artistic value of Chinese ethnic, folk, and classical dances, alongside Western ballet and representative forms. Through lectures, demonstrations, and comparative study, students explore dance history, theory, and aesthetic principles, enhancing their understanding and personal appreciation of diverse dance arts.
This course explores classical Chinese poetry through the lens of "imagery" (意象), the core aesthetic element conveying meaning beyond words. It analyzes six key poetic images—spring, autumn, moon, setting sun, countryside, and wine—to decode the creation of artistic conception. The approach moves beyond historical timelines, guiding students to appreciate, understand, and even compose poetry by mastering this essential poetic key.
This course analyzes 29 classic Chinese films from various eras. It systematically teaches film theory, examines case studies of renowned works, and develops students' comprehensive skills in film analysis and appreciation.
This course "Basketball—Basic Skills" covers seven core techniques: stance and movement, passing, dribbling, shooting, driving, rebounding, and physical conditioning. It explains concepts, demonstrates actions, and provides exercises to help students master theoretical knowledge, understand key structures and timing, and improve skills through practice, feedback, and correction for overall development.
This course introduces computational chemistry fundamentals, focusing on quantum chemical calculations to quantitatively understand chemical processes. Students will learn core theories and practical applications, equipping them with skills to analyze and solve chemical problems using computational methods.
This course integrates applied linguistics theory with practice, focusing on second language teaching—particularly Chinese. It covers key areas like language teaching theories, second language acquisition, teaching methodologies, and cultural aspects in instruction. Designed for aspiring teachers and graduate students, it aims to develop qualified Chinese language educators and support their teaching practice and research.
This foundational course for Teaching Chinese as a Foreign Language covers Chinese characters and vocabulary. It explores the origin, evolution, and ideographic nature of characters, alongside core lexical theories, analyzing the relationship between characters, morphemes, and words. The course aims to build a systematic knowledge framework and enhance analytical skills for both linguistic understanding and practical teaching applications.
This course introduces environmental planning principles, focusing on balancing human development with ecological sustainability. It explores strategies for land use, resource management, and ecosystem preservation to harmonize modern needs with natural systems. Students learn to design plans that protect biodiversity and promote long-term environmental health.
This course, "Solid Waste Disposal and Resource Recovery" (Spring 2019), provides foundational knowledge on solid waste characteristics, treatment technologies, and disposal methods. It combines theoretical principles with practical engineering applications and case studies, aiming to equip environmental engineering undergraduates with essential design and operational skills. The course features a rigorous assessment system and has been consistently highly rated by students.
This foundational course in journalism and communication focuses on news photography. It combines theoretical instruction in visual communication with practical training, using classic case studies to develop students' analytical, imitative, and innovative skills. The curriculum emphasizes hands-on practice, multimedia teaching methods, and fosters multi-layered dialogue through the critique of photographic works. Assessment is based on video assignments (60%) and a final exam (40%).
This course on Circular Economy and Sustainable Enterprises explores material flows within socioeconomic systems. Using discussion-based methods, it covers sustainable management, circular economy implementation, and enterprise development. The 14-session program enhances interdisciplinary research capabilities for cultivating innovative talents.
This course explores circular economy principles, focusing on material flows within socioeconomic systems. Through discussion-based teaching and simulated research processes, it covers sustainable management, material circulation, and building sustainable enterprises. The 14-session program enhances interdisciplinary innovation skills for students across humanities, sciences, and engineering fields.
This course introduces qualitative research methods for social sciences, focusing on theoretical foundations, practical application skills, and comparative analysis with quantitative approaches. It emphasizes participatory learning to develop critical research thinking and autonomous study capabilities, preparing students to design and implement qualitative research projects effectively.
This course offers an introduction to Kant's "Critique of Pure Reason" through close reading of key chapters. It focuses on developing students' ability to analyze philosophical texts, shift from knowledge acquisition to research-based learning, and enhance critical thinking regarding concepts and problems. Assessment includes regular exercises (60%) and a final exam (40%).
This course explores women's health through tailored nutrition and exercise across life stages. It covers physiological needs from adolescence to menopause, emphasizing how diet and physical activity enhance well-being, confidence, and empowerment. Practical knowledge is provided to foster holistic health and personal development for women.
This introductory tennis course (Spring 2019) teaches fundamental techniques and practice methods through eight units. It provides detailed instruction on basic strokes and error correction, aiming to help beginners master skills and appreciate tennis culture. The course grade is based 50% on assignments and 50% on a final exam.
This introductory waltz course (Spring 2019) teaches the foundational steps and elegant style of this classic ballroom dance. It focuses on developing proper posture, graceful movement, and rhythmic coordination. Students will gain basic dance skills, improve physical fitness, and cultivate confidence and social etiquette through practice. The course emphasizes the joyful and artistic experience of dance.
This course provides a comprehensive overview of the Winter Olympics, tracing its historical origins to modern developments. It explores the rich essence and unique appeal of the Games, offering a systematic introduction to the evolution and cultural significance of winter sports.
This course offers a comprehensive overview of the Winter Olympics, tracing its historical origins to modern developments. It explores the rich significance and unique appeal of the Games, providing a systematic introduction to the evolution and core spirit of winter sports.
This Evidence-Based Nursing course, led by Beijing University of Chinese Medicine's School of Nursing, focuses on integrating research evidence into clinical practice. It covers core principles and methodologies, supported by established research centers and international collaborations with JBI and BPSO. The curriculum emphasizes teaching, research, and practical application in nursing.
This Evidence-Based Nursing course, developed by Beijing University of Chinese Medicine's nursing faculty, focuses on integrating research evidence into clinical practice. Led by experts, it covers core principles and methodologies. The program supports the university's disciplinary development and is connected to international research centers like JBI and BPSO.
This course covers SaaS development using Agile methods and Ruby on Rails, focusing on cloud deployment, testing, and modern practices like TDD and pair programming. Students complete weekly projects to build and deploy a simple SaaS application.
This self-paced online course, "Grapes and Wine," offers a multidisciplinary introduction to wine over five weeks. Covering fundamentals from vineyard to cellar, it explores wine economics, history, and cultural exchange. Topics include winemaking processes, terroir management, climate change impacts, and global wine culture. Available in four languages, the course blends foundational knowledge with contemporary issues in viticulture and oenology.
This course explores medical devices and innovation in cardiovascular care. It covers clinical research trends and provides guidance for healthcare professionals to advance medical practices and foster developments in cardiovascular medicine.
This national-level quality course, "Road Engineering Materials," is a foundational undergraduate class for civil and transportation engineering. It systematically covers material theory and practice, integrating cutting-edge research and hands-on projects to develop students' technical skills, innovative thinking, and practical problem-solving abilities.
This course analyzes the common causes of entrepreneurial failure through real-world cases, exploring why startups often fail within years. It provides practical strategies and a four-step method to overcome setbacks, guiding entrepreneurs toward recognizing failure patterns and finding viable paths to eventual success.
This course, "Review: A Methodology for Unbeatable Entrepreneurship (Spring 2019)," teaches the core practice of "review" (fupan) as a systematic method for learning from past experiences. Originating from Lenovo, it emphasizes reflecting on actions and decisions to avoid repeating mistakes, transform experience into capability, and drive continuous improvement in fast-paced entrepreneurial environments.
This course, "Entrepreneurial Leadership: NASA's 4D Team Excellence," teaches the 4D system for building high-performance teams. It focuses on complementary talents, clear goals, effective systems, and strong culture, using assessments and workshops to enhance team dynamics and leadership, based on NASA's proven methodology.
This course explores the psychological foundations of innovation and entrepreneurship, focusing on cultivating a positive, resilient, and confident mindset. It provides practical psychological tools to inspire creativity, sustain motivation, and unlock the human drivers behind successful ventures.
This course provides a systematic introduction to project management, covering its historical development and key methodologies. It focuses on four critical aspects and eight essential elements for successful project execution, aiming to enhance learners' skills in selecting, evaluating, and managing projects to improve organizational efficiency and entrepreneurial success.
This course focuses on developing and presenting a business plan as the foundation for entrepreneurial success. It covers key steps: writing an effective plan, delivering compelling presentations, and continuously refining it. Featuring insights from experienced entrepreneurs and investors, the course provides practical guidance to help startups attract talent, secure funding, and map their growth strategy.
This course analyzes JD.com and Huawei's entrepreneurial journeys through case studies. It explores how JD transitioned to e-commerce and scaled operations, and examines Huawei's organizational culture and global strategy. Key themes include business model innovation, leadership during crises, securing investment, and building a strong corporate culture to drive growth and competitiveness in dynamic markets.
This course introduces the fundamentals of innovation and technology industrialization. It explores the importance of innovation in entrepreneurship and national development, using case studies like Kodak to highlight innovation management. The course aims to explain what innovation is, how to innovate, and how to effectively industrialize technology.
This course provides a comprehensive overview of infectious diseases. It covers fundamental concepts, including pathogenesis, epidemiology, diagnosis, treatment, and prevention. The curriculum details specific viral, bacterial, and parasitic infections, analyzing their etiology, clinical features, and management. It also addresses infection control, emerging diseases, and relevant public health legislation.
Structural Mechanics (Spring 2019) is a core foundational course for civil engineering and related majors. It bridges basic subjects like mathematics and material mechanics with advanced courses such as concrete and steel structure design. The course emphasizes both theoretical principles and engineering applications, building essential mechanical knowledge and professional skills.
"Fundamentals of Accounting" is a core course introducing essential accounting theories, principles, and practical skills. It covers basic concepts, double-entry bookkeeping, financial statement preparation, and accounting cycles. This foundational course equips students with the ability to understand and analyze business financial operations.
This course introduces digital electronic technology through cartoon-style explanations. It covers logic algebra, gate circuits, and the analysis/design of combinational and sequential logic circuits. Students learn principles and applications of common digital chips, pulse circuits, memory, A/D, and D/A converters. Emphasis is placed on practical problem-solving using medium-scale devices, building foundational skills for further studies.
This course introduces fundamental concepts of probability modeling and statistical inference, covering topics such as parameter estimation, hypothesis testing, and regression analysis. Through practical case studies and software applications, students develop skills in data analysis, scientific prediction, and decision-making, applying these methods to real-world scenarios in various fields. Basic calculus knowledge is required.
This course explores wedding culture as a comprehensive cultural system, examining its evolution through historical, literary, economic, and social lenses. It covers marriage rituals, beliefs, and regional variations, emphasizing how wedding culture reflects national identity. Students learn to appreciate its core role in both traditional and modern ceremonies, aiming to enhance professional understanding and cultural confidence while respecting heritage and fostering innovation.
This required course on college student mental health education covers eight key topics: self-awareness, emotion regulation, interpersonal relationships, love and sexuality, learning and creativity, personality development, life education, and career planning. It aims to enhance students' psychological well-being and equip them with skills to adapt to university life and manage stress effectively.
This course enhances international perspectives and cross-cultural communication skills through 16 thematic modules, including campus life, health, and global issues. It integrates lexical chunks, sentence patterns, discourse logic, and subject inquiry to develop language proficiency, critical thinking, and content knowledge systematically.
This self-paced thematic English course enhances university students' global perspectives and cross-cultural communication skills. It explores 16 diverse topics, including campus life, health, and technology. Each module develops language proficiency through lexical chunks, sentence patterns, discourse logic, and critical inquiry, progressing from language acquisition to advanced cognitive and analytical abilities.
This required course introduces medical students to cutting-edge experimental techniques and methods. It covers research design, cell biology, flow cytometry, molecular biology applications, immunohistochemistry, pharmacogenomics, and bioinformatics. The course emphasizes practical skills, scientific thinking, and foundational training for laboratory research, bridging basic science and clinical medicine.
This course cultivates students' ideological, moral, and legal foundations. It focuses on core socialist values, life philosophy, and patriotism. Students learn ethical conduct and gain essential knowledge of China's socialist legal system. The goal is to develop well-rounded individuals with strong moral character and rule-of-law awareness.
This course provides essential training in medical research design, covering key topics such as hypothesis formulation, research elements, statistical principles, error control, and strategies across disciplines like morphology and molecular biology. It complements medical statistics and is highly regarded for its expert-led, practical approach to designing high-quality experimental studies.
This graduate-level clinical epidemiology course introduces core concepts including study design, diagnostic testing, clinical trials, and outcome evaluation. It emphasizes applying epidemiological methods to clinical practice and research through multimedia teaching and case discussions. While popular, large class sizes limit interaction, suggesting blended learning could enhance student engagement and practical application.
This required course on college student mental health education covers eight key topics: self-awareness, emotion regulation, interpersonal relationships, love and sexuality, learning psychology, personality development, life education, and career planning. It aims to enhance students' psychological well-being, equip them with coping skills, and support their adaptation to university life.
This compulsory undergraduate course outlines major events in modern Chinese history, analyzing political shifts and their underlying causes. It fosters national identity and political awareness through historical study. The curriculum features thematic modules, integrates regional Hunan history for vivid case studies, and employs on-site teaching at revolutionary sites to enhance engagement.
This Molecular Biology course (Spring 2019) provides foundational knowledge in core theories, key techniques (like PCR and Western blotting), and modern applications in life sciences. Delivered via MOOC, it combines video lectures, animations, and assessments to foster scientific thinking and practical skills. Evaluation is based on chapter tests (60%) and a final exam (40%).
This Evidence-Based Medicine (2018 Winter Session) course trains medical postgraduates in critical thinking and EBM methods. It covers core topics like clinical guidelines, research methodology, and evidence appraisal, emphasizing the integration of best evidence with clinical expertise and patient values. Designed for autonomous online learning, it enhances students' ability to formulate accurate diagnosis and treatment plans through practical application.
This summer 2019 MOOC on Evidence-Based Medicine teaches clinical problem-solving through critical thinking. It equips medical postgraduates with skills to find, evaluate, and integrate the best evidence with clinical expertise and patient values for optimal diagnosis and treatment. The course covers principles, clinical guidelines, research methodology, and evidence appraisal, fostering autonomous learning and modern clinical research competencies.
This self-paced Evidence-Based Medicine course equips medical graduates with critical thinking and EBM methodologies. It covers core topics like clinical guidelines, research methods, and evidence appraisal, teaching students to integrate best evidence with clinical expertise and patient values for optimal healthcare decisions. The MOOC format enhances flexible, autonomous learning.
This course introduces fundamental theories and skills in medical information retrieval, covering Chinese databases, PubMed, and Web of Science. It focuses on literature search, citation management, and enhancing information literacy. Designed for diverse medical students, it employs multimedia, case studies, and PBL methods to develop analytical and self-learning abilities.
This course explores the fundamental elements of music from a beginner-friendly perspective, featuring live demonstrations. It analyzes how music functions in film, summarizing its role in storytelling. The curriculum investigates various methods for visualizing music and translating imagery into musical expression, adapting content from Berklee College of Music's certified online courses.
This course introduces new media concepts, historical evolution, and industry trends. It combines theory with practical skills, covering content creation, application techniques, and integration with fields like broadcasting and publishing. Students learn to design and produce new media projects, understanding both local and international contexts.
This course provides a comprehensive overview of cybersecurity, covering core topics including computer network fundamentals, key security issues, cryptography, security protocols, wireless network security, firewalls, and attack-defense systems. It offers foundational knowledge across essential areas of the field.
This core Petroleum Engineering course covers oil production fundamentals including inflow performance, wellbore flow, and nodal analysis. It introduces artificial lift methods like gas lift and rod pumping, along with stimulation techniques such as hydraulic fracturing. Students gain theoretical and practical knowledge of production systems and equipment. Assessment includes weekly assignments and a final exam.
This course, "Financial Statement Analysis: Logic and Techniques," focuses on analyzing the structure, relationships, and interpretation of four key financial statements. It covers essential methods, quality analysis frameworks, and practical skills. Designed for students and professionals, it combines theory with real-world cases and offers flexible learning modules. Assessment includes chapter quizzes and a final exam.
This course explores the cultural heritage of China's petroleum industry, examining its core values, historical evolution, and contemporary significance. It focuses on the unique ethical spirit and cultural identity within petroleum engineering, summarizing its development as a key part of China's industrial and spiritual legacy.
This self-paced course explores China's petroleum culture, a valuable spiritual legacy shaped by the nation's oil industry development. It summarizes the core concepts and historical evolution of this unique cultural heritage, while examining its contemporary significance and the ethical spirit within petroleum engineering.
This online course on Family Finance is open to all majors and grades. It employs project-based teaching with group activities, case studies, financial scenarios, and skill competitions. Students learn financial knowledge online, role-play as financial planners, and enhance interaction and practical financial skills.
This "Fundamentals of Innovation and Entrepreneurship" course, based on Dr. Sun Hongyi's award-winning 3333 syllabus and PIPE model, systematically integrates creativity, innovation, and entrepreneurship. Designed for all students, it focuses on practical learning outcomes: identifying problems, generating ideas, developing solutions, and creating basic business plans to cultivate essential innovative and entrepreneurial mindsets and skills.
This supplementary course focuses on series, multivariable calculus, and ordinary differential equations. It aims to deepen students' mastery of calculus concepts, mathematical thinking, and precise application of mathematical language to solve concrete problems.
This course teaches how to analyze financial statements using a four-step diagnostic approach: observing economic impacts, detecting industry changes, questioning data meanings, and interpreting company performance. It covers the three main financial statements, accounting standards, and how management decisions affect reporting, equipping investors and stakeholders with essential skills for informed financial decision-making.
This course teaches how to analyze financial statements using a four-step diagnostic approach: observing economic impacts, detecting industry trends, questioning data meanings, and interpreting company performance. It covers the three main financial statements, accounting standards, and how management decisions affect reporting. Designed for investors, creditors, and stakeholders to make informed financial decisions.
This course teaches the design of complete photovoltaic systems, focusing on converting solar energy into electricity. It covers solar cell operation, manufacturing, and various technologies like crystalline silicon and thin-film. Students learn to design practical PV systems through instructional videos, exercises, and exams, using provided textbook materials.
This course systematically covers principles and methods of test system integration. Key topics include digital interfaces for programmable instruments, SCPI command syntax/format, and measurement controller design. Students learn to select instruments, build automated test systems, and develop practical testing software through hands-on operation.
This self-paced course explores parasites as significant pathogens impacting human and animal health, focusing on zoonotic parasites and associated diseases. It covers an overview of parasites in public health, along with foodborne, soilborne, pet-related, and travel-associated parasitic infections. The course aims to enhance awareness and promote personal protection. Assessment includes chapter quizzes (60%) and a final exam (40%).
This course explores the world of insects through postage stamps, blending natural science with cultural symbolism. It examines diverse insect species, their unique survival strategies, and their rich cultural representations in literature and history, from ancient Chinese poetry to Western mythology.
This course focuses on "Optimistic Intelligence," the core of positive psychology, which involves cultivating optimism, resilience, and the ability to positively influence others. It covers practical skills for enhancing psychological well-being, empathy, and social productivity through interactive lectures on self-identity, humor, morality, and personal growth.
This course introduces common parasites impacting human and animal health, focusing on zoonotic diseases. It covers foodborne, soilborne, pet-related, and travel-associated parasitic infections to raise public awareness and enhance prevention. Assessment includes chapter quizzes (60%) and a final exam (40%).
This course provides systematic sex education for university students, covering biological, psychological, and social dimensions of sexuality. It aims to demystify sex, impart essential knowledge, prevent sexually transmitted diseases, and foster healthy sexual attitudes and behaviors. The curriculum supports personal development and prepares students for relationships and family life.
This course introduces Health Informatics through the lens of traditional Chinese medicine (TCM). It explores TCM's historical evolution, key concepts like preventive care from classical texts, and the wisdom of ancient physicians. The content connects these foundations to modern information technology applications in healthcare, aiming to inspire student interest and innovation in the field.
This introductory economics course covers fundamental microeconomic and macroeconomic principles. It examines individual economic units like households and firms in microeconomics, including supply-demand theory and market structures. Macroeconomics analyzes national economies, exploring topics such as GDP measurement, the IS-LM model, and fiscal policies. The course provides essential analytical tools for understanding economic decision-making and aggregate trends.
This course introduces investment banking fundamentals, covering core concepts, functions, and key operations such as securities issuance, trading, mergers and acquisitions, asset securitization, venture capital, and asset management. It emphasizes business characteristics, operational principles, and regulatory frameworks, equipping students with practical knowledge for future careers or research in the field.
This Financial Engineering course introduces core derivative instruments (forwards, futures, options, swaps), their pricing models, and hedging applications. It equips students with financial engineering theories and technical methods—including mathematical modeling and simulation—to design financial products and develop risk management strategies, fostering analytical problem-solving skills in finance.
This self-paced Financial Engineering course covers core derivatives like forwards, futures, options, and swaps, focusing on their pricing and use in hedging. It introduces financial engineering theories and techniques, applying mathematical modeling and simulation to design financial products and manage risks, cultivating analytical problem-solving skills in finance.
This course explores Internet finance, focusing on applying information and network technologies to transform traditional financial services. It covers key areas like P2P lending, crowdfunding, digital currency, and online banking, while examining their economic impact, risks, and regulatory challenges. Students will develop practical skills to analyze real-world financial issues innovatively.
This course provides a macro-level understanding of financial markets, institutions, and central banking. It explores the nature, creation, and impact of money, covering interest rates, commercial banking, money supply and demand, and monetary policy mechanisms and strategies in an open economy.
This course introduces disaster risk management principles, covering risk assessment, analysis, and mitigation strategies. It explores hazard identification, vulnerability analysis, and decision-making processes, along with risk control measures and financial tools like catastrophe insurance. The interdisciplinary approach equips students with practical frameworks to address real-world disaster risks.
This course introduces crystal optics, focusing on how light interacts with transparent mineral crystals, including phenomena like refraction, polarization, and interference. It covers the use of polarizing microscopes and optical indicatrices to identify minerals, combining theoretical foundations with practical applications in mineralogy and petrology.
This self-paced course, "Monetary Finance," explores the core mechanisms of modern economies. It covers financial markets, institutions, and central banking, focusing on the nature, creation, and impact of money. Key topics include interest rates, commercial banking, money supply and demand, and the theory and implementation of monetary policy in an open economy.
This general education course, "Music Stroll," explores interdisciplinary approaches to music appreciation through eight theoretical dimensions. It emphasizes rational engagement leading to emotional reflection, focusing not on technical understanding but on personal connection and diverse perspectives. The course aims to foster holistic development, encouraging students to enjoy an artistic life regardless of their academic background.
Circuit Principles is a foundational course for electrical and information majors, introducing core circuit theory. It covers basic concepts and analytical methods, equipping students with skills to solve fundamental electronic and electrical engineering problems, preparing them for advanced studies.
"Circuit Principles" is a foundational course for electrical and information majors, introducing core circuit theory. It focuses on developing analytical skills, problem-solving abilities, and key knowledge in circuit analysis. The course equips students with essential tools to address basic electrical engineering challenges, preparing them for advanced studies in the field.
This self-paced "Introduction to Computational Thinking" course explores the essence of computational thinking as a problem-solving methodology. It addresses key educational challenges, distinguishing it from basic computer science. The curriculum focuses on core problem-solving techniques used in computing and their application across various disciplines to foster innovation and system design.
This course, "Outline of Modern Chinese History," is a compulsory undergraduate course in ideological and political theory. It combines online and flipped classroom learning, featuring interactive video lectures that restructure textbook content into a logical, value-oriented question system. The innovative format enhances understanding of historical frameworks and achieves cognitive, skill-based, and emotional teaching objectives.
This course, "Outline of Modern Chinese History," is a compulsory undergraduate course in ideological and political theory, also available as an elective. It employs a blended online-offline (flipped classroom) approach, featuring interactive video lectures where three instructors collaboratively restructure textbook content into a logical, value-oriented question system. The format innovatively combines elements of talk shows and academic forums, aiming to achieve cognitive, skill-based, and emotional learning objectives through educational, practical, and developmental teaching methods.
This course explores the essence of life and death, addressing topics like the psychology of dying, end-of-life care, euthanasia, and societal issues related to death. It aims to demystify death, foster a sacred perspective on life's finitude, and encourage reflection on living meaningfully by confronting mortality.
This self-paced course, "Life and Death Studies," systematically explores the essence of death, dying processes, and end-of-life psychology. It examines individual and societal death, grief, and ethical issues like euthanasia. By demystifying death, the course encourages reflection on life's value to promote personal growth and a dignified existence.
This course introduces dynamic geometry, which explores geometric figures maintaining relationships during motion. Using China's Super Sketchpad software, it demonstrates mathematical concepts through animation, tracking, and iteration. Covering plane geometry, functions, and 3D shapes, the course makes math intuitive and engaging by blending logic with visual experimentation.
This core printing course covers color theory and practical skills essential for printing production. It explores color formation, attributes, representation, and printing-specific color characteristics. Students learn to identify, adjust, mix spot colors, and evaluate print color quality through case studies and hands-on projects, simplifying complex concepts into actionable steps.
This core printing course covers color theory and practical skills essential for the industry. It explores color formation, properties, representation, and printing-specific color characteristics. Students learn to identify, adjust, mix spot colors, and evaluate print color quality through case studies and hands-on projects, simplifying complex concepts into actionable steps.
This course explores entrepreneurship in the pharmaceutical and healthcare sectors. It focuses on identifying innovative opportunities, developing business models, and integrating resources. Through expert interviews and case studies, it examines real-world scenarios and key topics like AI in healthcare and China's health policies, guided by contemporary theoretical frameworks.
This self-paced Organic Chemistry course provides fundamental knowledge in hydrocarbons, functional groups, stereochemistry, and key compounds. It emphasizes theoretical understanding, practical skills, and problem-solving abilities, integrating modern research and interdisciplinary applications to prepare students for advanced studies in chemistry, life sciences, and engineering.
This undergraduate elective course explores the integration of 5G and artificial intelligence, covering their foundational concepts and future applications. It prepares students from all majors for emerging careers in these fields by connecting technical knowledge with current national strategies and economic trends, presented in an accessible yet insightful manner.
This advanced programming course focuses on practical data objects in real-world contexts, emphasizing data storage and processing methods. It strengthens skills in C language functions, pointers, strings, structures, and dynamic memory allocation, guiding students to master data operations and structured programming. This foundation supports further studies in data structures, operating systems, databases, and computer architecture.
This course covers fundamental analog electronic technology, focusing on semiconductor devices like diodes, transistors, and integrated circuits, along with key circuits such as amplifiers, operational amplifiers, and signal processing. It offers digital resources, including 100 micro-lectures and a synchronized textbook, providing an interactive learning experience through quizzes, discussions, and online support.
This course, "High-Frequency Electronic Circuits," is a core foundational subject for majors like Electronic Information Engineering. It covers key topics including high-frequency amplifiers, oscillators, modulation/demodulation, and feedback control circuits. Delivered through concise video lectures and interactive online resources, the course emphasizes both theoretical principles and practical engineering applications.
This self-paced Engineering Graphics course focuses on expressing and communicating engineering and product information through technical drawings. It develops skills in 2D/3D spatial visualization, drafting, and design, while emphasizing standards compliance and engineering thinking for technical applications.
This spring 2019 course introduces watercolor painting techniques and expressive methods. It covers essential tools, paper stretching, basic and special techniques, as well as approaches for still life and landscape subjects.
This course, "Art Appreciation (Spring 2019)," is a general education class based on Gombrich's "The Story of Art." It surveys Western art from prehistory to the 20th century, exploring how cultural and historical contexts shape artistic expression. Students develop cross-cultural thinking and critical insight by examining the cultural and era-specific values in artworks. The course aims to enhance aesthetic experience, connecting it to creation, appreciation, and daily life, thereby unlocking creative potential.
This course covers construction project management fundamentals, including project procedures, schedule control, quality assurance, cost management, safety, environmental compliance, and contract administration. It equips students with essential theories and practical skills to address real-world engineering project challenges.
This course focuses on low-frequency electronic circuits, covering electronic components, basic and feedback amplifier circuits, and integrated operational amplifiers with their applications. Emphasizing core concepts like amplification and practical analysis methods, it integrates theory with engineering practice to enhance problem-solving skills. The course features high-quality instructional videos with animations for intuitive learning.
This core accounting course covers the fundamental theories and design principles of accounting information systems. Students learn system development, data storage, input/output design, and key modules like ledger, voucher, and report management. The focus is on enduring concepts that remain consistent across evolving platforms, providing a solid theoretical foundation for practical application.
This course introduces curling, a sport originating in 16th-century Scotland that has evolved into a global Olympic discipline. It covers the history, equipment, techniques, tactics, and rules of curling. Students will gain foundational knowledge to appreciate and participate in the sport, fostering an understanding of its development and China's achievements in international competitions.
This self-paced curling course covers the sport's origins in 16th-century Scotland, its global development, and Olympic status. It introduces equipment, techniques, tactics, rules, and major competitions. Students will gain foundational knowledge for playing and appreciating curling, fostering an understanding of its history and a lifelong engagement with the sport.
This self-paced alpine skiing course explores the evolution of skiing from ancient transportation to a modern recreational sport. It covers the origins and development of alpine skiing in the European Alps, focusing on techniques, equipment like skis and poles, and its transformation into a globally popular competitive and leisure activity.
This course explores the musical tradition of classical Chinese poetry, from the Book of Songs to Song lyrics, highlighting their rhythmic and melodic features. It integrates historical scores and modern interpretations to revive ancient recitation styles, offering both analysis and artistic appreciation.
This course provides a foundational overview of Marxist theory, focusing on its core principles. Key topics include the laws governing the material world, the processes of understanding and transforming reality, and the fundamental patterns of societal development. The aim is to equip students with a scientific worldview and values based on these principles.
This course explores the power of design through the lens of human design history, focusing on pivotal events over the past 250 years. It examines design's critical role in national development and its current importance in driving innovation, transforming China's manufacturing image, and supporting the transition to an innovation-driven economy.
This course examines modern Chinese history, focusing on key events and figures to analyze the patterns of social development, revolution, and reform. It explores how China chose Marxism, the Communist Party, socialism, and reform, fostering confidence in the nation's history and socialist path.
This course introduces the artistic and cultural aspects of ancient Chinese architecture, covering palaces, gardens, temples, and residential structures. Using visual aids, it explains their historical and philosophical significance in an accessible way, aiming to enhance appreciation for these cultural heritage sites without technical architectural details. Suitable for all backgrounds.
This course offers an in-depth exploration of Sun Tzu's "The Art of War," a foundational Chinese military classic. It examines its historical significance, core principles, and enduring relevance in strategy and leadership. Designed for all students, the course aims to enhance cultural literacy and critical thinking skills through the study of this timeless text.
This self-paced Modern Etiquette course, taught by Professor Yuan Difei, covers eight key areas: introduction, personal image, daily life, conversation, workplace, social interactions, dining, and international etiquette. Combining theory with practical guidance, it enhances personal修养 and social skills through weekly videos, exercises, and a final paper.
This course explores the scientific principles behind exercise and health, focusing on effective fitness, weight management, and posture correction. It teaches how to evaluate exercise methods and design personalized workout plans, addressing common myths and providing practical guidance for both men and women.
This course offers an appreciation of Chinese traditional opera, focusing on its artistic and cultural essence. It aims to enhance students' aesthetic perception, cultural awareness, and artistic literacy by exploring opera history and stage art, fostering a deeper understanding of China's unique cultural heritage.
This course introduces the fundamental principles of Marxism, covering its worldview, methodology, and analysis of societal development. It aims to equip students with the ability to apply Marxist theory to analyze and solve practical problems, fostering a scientific outlook on the world, life, and values. The curriculum includes video lectures, discussions, and assessments.
This course covers essential business etiquette and communication skills, including job interviews, professional appearance, meetings, and correspondence. Through practical case studies, it enhances students' interpersonal abilities and competitiveness in modern social and professional settings.
This self-paced course on Intellectual Property Law and Innovation Protection covers core areas including patents, trademarks, copyrights, and trade secrets. It provides foundational theories, case studies, and practical strategies to enhance risk awareness and protection skills in the digital age, suitable for students, professionals, and entrepreneurs.
This self-paced English Phonetics course covers core elements including vowels, consonants, connected speech, stress, and intonation. Designed for first-year English majors, it systematically introduces essential pronunciation knowledge. Through dedicated study, students can build a foundational understanding and improve their spoken accuracy, though mastery requires ongoing practice beyond the course.
This course offers an introductory study of Brazilian Portuguese, focusing on essential grammar, vocabulary, and pronunciation for daily communication. It covers practical dialogues, key sentence structures, and cultural insights from Portuguese-speaking countries, building a solid foundation in the language.
This self-paced university Portuguese course focuses on Brazilian Portuguese, covering essential pronunciation, vocabulary, grammar, and daily conversation skills. It includes bilingual dialogues, cultural insights from Portuguese-speaking countries, and builds a solid foundation for basic communication.
This self-paced course covers fundamental circuit analysis using R, L, C components, Kirchhoff's laws, and equivalent transformations to determine voltage, current, and power. It introduces transient analysis with dynamic elements and sinusoidal steady-state analysis via phasors. Combining theoretical videos with simulation and hands-on lab demonstrations, it enhances practical skills in electrical engineering basics for non-electrical majors.
This self-paced Environmental Ecology course focuses on applying ecological principles to conserve natural resources, manage pollution, restore damaged ecosystems, and balance environmental protection with economic development for sustainable human needs.
This course introduces real estate development and management in China, covering key processes, market analysis, feasibility studies, risk assessment, and marketing strategies. It combines theory with practical skills, serving as a foundation for advanced real estate studies and professional practice.
This course, "Inorganic Chemistry (Spring 2019)," is a provincial-level quality course in Hubei. It innovatively integrates online video lectures with a dedicated WeChat public account. This platform provides detailed explanations, supplements, and expanded knowledge, transforming the course into an effective, multi-modal teaching tool that enhances student engagement and learning outcomes.
This course, "The Art of Management Communication," teaches essential communication skills for effective management. It covers fundamental principles, verbal and non-verbal strategies, and practical applications in scenarios like cross-cultural communication, negotiation, and conflict resolution. Designed for students and professionals, the course emphasizes both knowledge and practice to enhance workplace and interpersonal communication, supporting career development.
Engineering Graphics (Spring 2019) introduces the theory and application of technical drawings in engineering. It covers projection methods, geometric representation, and the creation/interpretation of engineering blueprints. The course develops spatial imagination, analytical skills, and precise engineering thinking, serving as a foundational tool for professional technical communication and design.
This course explores the relationship between physical activity and health from an interdisciplinary perspective, integrating sports humanities, exercise science, and medicine. It covers scientific exercise methods, health benefits of various sports, injury prevention, and management. The goal is to equip students with knowledge for lifelong healthy living through regular, informed physical activity.
This self-paced course explores the vital link between physical activity and health. It covers the scientific principles of exercise, effective fitness methods, and injury prevention. Through instructional videos and myth clarification, learners gain practical knowledge to develop safe, personalized routines for enhancing well-being.
This online course "Sports and Anatomy" is a foundational undergraduate requirement. It features 35 interactive modules and 65 gamified tasks designed to engage learners. The curriculum systematically covers core anatomical knowledge, reinforced by chapter tests with set proficiency standards. It supports large-scale, multi-disciplinary online learning.
This Financial Statement Analysis course (Spring 2019) teaches practical skills for interpreting corporate financial reports. It moves beyond basic ratio analysis, using real-world cases to evaluate company performance, assess risks, and support decision-making in areas like valuation and investment. The curriculum covers analysis steps, fraud detection, and applying insights to strategic and managerial decisions.
This self-paced course provides Chinese speakers an introductory approach to Spanish language and Hispanic culture. Using communicative methods, it covers everyday situations like self-introductions, ordering food, and shopping. Cultural insights and language learning strategies are emphasized to build foundational skills in an engaging manner.
This course surveys ancient Chinese literature from pre-Qin to the Six Dynasties. It covers key works like the Book of Songs, Chu Ci, historical prose, and the Records of the Grand Historian. Students explore major authors such as Qu Yuan and Tao Yuanming, analyzing literary development, artistic achievements, and historical context.
This course surveys the evolution of world civilizations. It covers the origins and diverse development of ancient societies, the transformation of medieval cultures, and the modernization of Western civilization—highlighting the Renaissance, Reformation, and Enlightenment. It further examines modern Western prosperity and contemporary multicultural conflicts and integration, including key 20th-century events and global trends.
This course introduces Private International Law, focusing on resolving civil legal conflicts across different countries and jurisdictions. It covers core concepts, principles, and methods for addressing cross-border civil disputes, such as marriage, divorce, and property division involving multiple legal systems. Designed with an outcomes-based approach, it aims to build a solid foundation for handling international civil matters.
This course explores marriage and family issues from a legal perspective, focusing on the Marriage Law. It analyzes legal relationships—both personal and property—within modern families, alongside emotional dynamics. Using legal reasoning, it aims to foster balanced interactions among family members to achieve equitable, harmonious, and civilized relationships. Students will learn to apply rational legal principles in emotional contexts.
This introductory course explores mechanics' fundamental role in science and modern life. It covers static, dynamic, and fluid mechanics principles, applying them to aerospace, engineering, and daily phenomena. Designed for non-specialists, it aims to build scientific literacy and analytical skills for interpreting natural and technological challenges.
This general education course explores ecological security and nature conservation, addressing global environmental degradation, climate change impacts, and ecological crises. It covers fundamental concepts, China's conservation status, and global hotspots, aiming to cultivate environmental stewardship and awareness. Recognized as a national quality course, it integrates award-winning multimedia resources.
This general education course explores ecological conservation and security, addressing global environmental degradation, climate change impacts, and threats to Earth's ecosystems. It covers fundamental concepts, China's conservation status, and global hotspots, aiming to cultivate environmental awareness and responsibility. Recognized as a national quality course, it integrates award-winning digital resources.
This course explores the fundamental principles of cell biology, examining cellular structure, function, and molecular regulation. It adopts a "cellular society" perspective to analyze internal organization, external communication, and the entire life cycle of cells. The curriculum integrates core knowledge with cutting-edge advancements, aiming to inspire innovation and a deeper understanding of life processes.
This self-paced course covers essential safety knowledge for biomedical laboratories, including chemistry, biology, medicine, and related fields. It provides comprehensive training on general safety, electrical, water, gas, fire, chemical, biological, and animal handling hazards, along with prevention measures, emergency response, and fire drills to enhance safety awareness and reduce accidents.
This course introduces management consulting from a consultant's perspective, focusing on helping businesses identify and resolve internal and external management challenges. It covers historical and modern consulting practices, diagnostic methods like investigation-analysis-judgment, and solution design. Emphasizing real-world applications, it integrates case studies for practical learning, suitable for senior students and professionals.
This course "Civil Law and Daily Life" explores how civil law governs everyday interactions through fundamental concepts, systems, and theories. Using real cases, it covers personal rights (e.g., privacy, reputation) and property rights (e.g., contracts, ownership), along with legal protections against infringement. Emphasizing principles like good faith and contractual spirit, it teaches individuals to assert and respect rights in daily scenarios.
This course explores the time value of money as a core concept in modern finance, integrating principles from psychology and daily life. It covers fundamental concepts, calculations, and practical applications using financial calculators. Through real-world investment examples, the course enhances financial literacy and decision-making skills for personal and professional growth.
This course introduces traditional Chinese medicine (TCM) theories, including Yin-Yang, Five Elements, and organ systems, and focuses on TCM diagnostic methods such as observation, listening, questioning, and pulse-taking. It aims to equip learners with practical skills for self-health assessment and basic TCM application, supported by online resources and interactive sessions.
This introductory course on Traditional Chinese Medicine (TCM) and Diagnostics teaches core TCM theories—including Yin-Yang, Five Elements, and Qi-Blood-Fluid—and practical diagnostic methods like inspection, listening, questioning, and pulse-taking. Designed for beginners, it enables students to apply TCM principles for self-health assessment and basic understanding of diagnostics.
This Mathematical Modeling course, launched in 2006, teaches practical methods and techniques through case studies. It covers applying mathematical models—from basic to advanced, like optimization and analytic hierarchy process—to solve real-world problems in daily life, science, and engineering. The course emphasizes innovative thinking and has a strong track record in national competitions.
This course introduces engaging Chinese teaching methodologies, covering their design principles, types, and applications. Students learn to create interactive activities like tongue twisters, songs, and games tailored to language components and skills. Emphasis is placed on practical teaching abilities through theory,案例分析, and hands-on lesson design.
This course introduces engaging Chinese teaching methodologies, covering their design principles, objectives, and practical applications. Students learn to create interactive activities like tongue twisters, songs, and games tailored to language components and skills. Emphasis is placed on developing practical instructional design and implementation abilities through theory, analysis, and hands-on practice.
This course explores spatial art in "Dream of the Red Chamber," focusing on architectural spaces (visual culture) and fragrance spaces (olfactory culture). It analyzes how courtyards, gardens, and scents convey artistic expression and cultural values. Through cross-disciplinary comparisons, it examines elements like layout, doors, walls, and character-specific fragrance tones, revealing their narrative functions and symbolic meanings in the novel.
This self-paced Art Psychology course explores visual perception and social psychology in art. It examines how artistic forms create psychological effects, blending theory with practical analysis of artworks. Through 12 concise lectures, it emphasizes empirical approaches and human-centered methodologies, fostering independent research skills while connecting professional concepts to universal human experiences.
This graduate-level AI course covers core concepts including search algorithms, constraint satisfaction, game theory, Bayesian networks, and machine learning models. It provides essential theoretical foundations for intelligent systems, with a focus on algorithmic implementation and practical applications in fields like pattern recognition and data analysis.
This graduate-level AI course covers core topics including search algorithms, constraint satisfaction, game theory, Bayesian networks, and machine learning models. Designed for computer science majors, it emphasizes algorithmic foundations and practical programming to equip students with essential theoretical knowledge for intelligent systems and data analysis applications.
This course focuses on teaching Chinese as a heritage language to overseas Chinese communities. It systematically covers the theoretical foundations, historical development, and current practices of Chinese language education abroad. The course aims to equip teachers with advanced teaching concepts and effective methods to enhance heritage language transmission. It distinguishes itself from general Teaching Chinese as a Foreign Language courses by emphasizing the unique needs of ethnic Chinese learners.
This course provides essential workplace etiquette training for career beginners. It covers ten key modules including professional image, business communication, meeting protocols, and interview skills. Through practical demonstrations and scenario-based learning, students develop polished manners and interpersonal competencies to enhance their professional effectiveness in diverse business settings.
This course provides a concise introduction to 3ds Max 2019, focusing on essential 3D modeling, rendering, and animation techniques. It covers fundamental operations, practical modeling methods, lighting, materials, basic animation, and an overview of VR/AR workflows. Designed for beginners, it aims to build a solid foundation for game design, virtual reality, interior design, and film production.
This course introduces the fundamental principles and techniques of genetic engineering, covering gene cloning, vector systems, recombinant DNA technology, and sequencing. It emphasizes practical applications in biotechnology and molecular biology, equipping students with essential theoretical knowledge and experimental skills for genetic research.
This course introduces the fundamental principles and techniques of genetic engineering, covering gene cloning, vector systems, recombinant DNA technology, and applications. It integrates knowledge from biochemistry, microbiology, and molecular biology, aiming to equip students with both theoretical understanding and basic experimental skills for future research in the field.
This course provides comprehensive guidance on nurturing a healthy baby, covering topics from pre-pregnancy preparation and prenatal care to childbirth. It addresses physiological changes, nutrition, and psychological adjustments during pregnancy, incorporating modern medical techniques. Designed for expectant parents, including older couples, it emphasizes life appreciation and family collaboration, using expert-led animations and real-life cases to deliver accessible yet professional knowledge.
This course "Marketing in Daily Life" explores fundamental marketing principles through real-world examples. It covers market research, competitive strategies, segmentation, and the 4P's marketing mix. Blending theory with practical cases, it demonstrates how marketing shapes everyday decisions and business success. Assessment combines regular assignments (40%) and final evaluation (60%).
This self-paced course, "Marketing in Daily Life," demystifies marketing by revealing its principles in everyday activities. It covers core topics like market research, competitive strategy, targeting, and the marketing mix (4Ps), blending theory with real-world cases. The course illustrates that marketing is both a science and an art, emphasizing its practical impact and omnipresence in personal and organizational decisions.
This course focuses on academic English for science and engineering. It covers eight key modules: academic reading, writing, listening, speaking, technical translation, vocabulary, and grammar. The instruction is based on content-based learning principles to enhance professional communication skills in technical fields.
This course explores the mysteries of subconscious psychology from a metacognitive perspective. It scientifically explains common psychological issues and disorders among college students, as well as the mental structures behind genius inspiration and positive personality traits. The course aims to enhance students' self-awareness, monitoring, reflection, and regulation of subconscious processes, thereby improving the effectiveness of mental health education.
This course explores subconscious psychology through metacognitive intervention techniques. It scientifically explains common psychological issues and gifted states in college students, enhancing their self-awareness and regulation of subconscious processes to improve mental health education effectiveness.
This public elective course introduces film appreciation to undergraduate students. It explores eight thematic modules of selected Chinese and international films, analyzing artistic features, directorial styles, and performance techniques. The course aims to enhance students' aesthetic judgment, artistic literacy, and ability to critically evaluate cinema, while fostering positive values through the enduring魅力 of film art.
This professional course on Exhibition Planning and Management equips students with essential skills in event preparation, execution, and post-event management. Designed for industry professionals and students, it integrates real-world standards and practical workflows to prepare learners for advanced roles in the exhibition sector.
This course systematically explores Chinese folk culture through life rituals, festivals, production, diet, clothing, housing, transportation, recreation, and beliefs. Using rich visual materials, it examines their origins, evolution, and modern forms. Students will gain deep insight into cultural traditions, enhancing their understanding, appreciation, and responsibility for preserving this heritage.
This course explores modern Chinese social changes through the historical transformation of Lushun. It highlights how national fortunes shape regional destinies, using local stories and sites as an open-air museum. The curriculum fosters patriotism by linking historical reflection with contemporary responsibility, inspiring students to contribute to national rejuvenation.
This public elective course introduces Chinese floral culture and indoor plant cultivation. Students learn plant types, container selection, soil management, watering techniques, and pest control. It covers decorative arrangements for various spaces, focusing on scale, color coordination, and artistic planting methods. The course also touches on feng shui principles for indoor plant placement, aiming to develop both theoretical knowledge and practical skills for creating harmonious green interiors.
This course introduces the core principles of Marxism, focusing on its scientific approach to fostering comprehensive human development. It explores the historical context, key ideas of Marx and Engels, and the foundational theories of Marxism as a guiding philosophy.
This introductory Linux course covers major distributions, teaching graphical interface and command-line proficiency. It highlights Linux's widespread use in servers, finance, and Android devices, along with career advantages. Designed for all skill levels, the course equips learners with essential tools for system administration, programming, or general use.
This course provides a concise introduction to the 14 land neighbors of China, including North Korea, Russia, Mongolia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Afghanistan, India, Pakistan, Myanmar, Nepal, Bhutan, Laos, and Vietnam. It covers their basic national profiles, geographical features, and cultural highlights, offering insights into the countries along China's extensive land borders.
This self-paced course provides an introduction to China's 14 land neighbors, including Russia, India, Pakistan, and North Korea. It covers their key geographical, cultural, and historical characteristics, highlighting their significance along China's extensive 22,000 km land border. The focus is on understanding these neighboring nations' basic profiles and regional roles.
This course examines land readjustment as an alternative land assembly method in developing countries. It explores how landowners contribute land as capital in exchange for plots post-redevelopment, minimizing displacement and conflicts. The course highlights its advantages for urban development, including lower capital requirements and reduced resistance. Assessment consists of 18 multiple-choice questions.
This course teaches how to evaluate socially responsible real estate development using Social Impact Assessment (SIA) and Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) tools. Through case studies, participants learn to apply these assessments and public consultation to analyze projects, develop personal principles for responsible development, and create value for stakeholders.
This course focuses on developing products that meet customer needs and deliver value. Through case studies across various industries, it explores how to create strong value propositions, identify competitive advantages, and understand market dynamics. The core theme is shifting perspective from what customers can do for you to what you can do for them.
This course focuses on developing products that meet customer needs and deliver value. Through case studies across various industries, it explores how to define product concepts, establish clear value propositions, and build competitive advantages. The core theme is shifting perspective from what customers can do for you to what you can do for them.
This MIT course focuses on identifying and understanding customers as the core of entrepreneurship. Through real case studies, students learn to identify, interview, and select the right customers for their ventures. It offers practical steps to transform ideas into viable businesses, emphasizing that customers are the most crucial resource for startup success.
This course introduces MIT's U-Theory to help leaders navigate systemic change. It focuses on developing self-awareness, deep listening, and collaborative skills to address complex societal challenges. Participants learn to move from sensing to prototyping new solutions, applying these methods to real-world issues through global co-creation.
This 90-minute introductory course explores U-Theory, a methodology for awareness-based systemic change. It teaches foundational concepts for sensing and co-creating emerging futures, enabling individuals and organizations to translate inspiration into tangible transformation. Participants join a global community of practitioners to drive cross-boundary change through deepened self-awareness and collective leadership.
This introductory MIT-level course covers the dynamics of particles and rigid bodies, analyzing motion, forces, and trajectories in mechanical systems. Students learn to apply Newtonian mechanics, solve problems using MATLAB and numerical methods, and examine rotational dynamics, torque, and system imbalances. It builds foundational engineering skills through practical applications.
This self-paced MITx course covers fundamental circuit and electronics concepts, including resistive networks, transistors, digital abstraction, amplifiers, and first/second-order dynamics. It emphasizes the lumped circuit abstraction and includes design exercises, labs, homework, and exams. Successful completion leads to an honor code certificate.
This introductory computer science course teaches computational thinking and Python programming for beginners. It covers fundamental concepts, basic algorithms, data structures, testing, debugging, and algorithmic complexity. Designed as a broad overview rather than an in-depth specialization, it equips students with foundational knowledge to solve problems using computation.
This course offers an appreciation of Chinese ethnic minority myths, focusing on the 55 minority groups. It explores their ideological depth, artistic styles, and the spirit of unity within diversity in Chinese culture. Through cross-cultural comparisons with Han and foreign myths, it provides an engaging, insightful study. Assessment includes video quizzes (60%) and a final exam (40%).
This course introduces the development, key figures, and works of visual anthropology, covering its core theories, methods, and contemporary significance. It is valuable for students in anthropology, ethnology, film, and media studies. Assessment includes chapter quizzes (60%) and a final exam (40%), with grades out of 100.
This course offers four lectures on Tang Dynasty history, focusing on its territorial concepts, north-south integration, and the Sinicization of Sogdian immigrants as reflected in epitaphs. It analyzes the dynasty's governance, social structures, and cultural assimilation through specific case studies, aiming to enhance students' historical understanding and humanistic literacy.
This self-paced course explores the scientific principles behind various natural disasters, examining their causes, global impacts, and interconnections. It focuses on understanding the limits and possibilities of human efforts in prediction and mitigation. Students will learn how to apply this knowledge to reduce disaster risks, essential for fields like urban planning, emergency management, and policy-making.
This self-paced course explores the molecular composition of macro- and micronutrients, using scientific perspectives to clarify prevalent food controversies. It examines the relationships between diet, cancer, cardiovascular disease, and body weight, while addressing foodborne illnesses and additives. Students will learn to assess nutritional information, evaluate media reports on food research, and critically analyze issues in food production and health claims.
This online course features a six-part lecture series on big data fundamentals and applications, delivered by senior researchers from Microsoft Research Asia and Tsinghua University professors. Presented in English with subtitles, it covers core concepts like volume, velocity, and variety in big data, offering insights into its transformative impact on computer science and society.
This course focuses on practical skills in labor relations, covering key areas such as employment procedures, contract management, dispute resolution, and compliance with labor standards. Designed for HR roles in small to medium enterprises, it uses case-based scenarios, expert insights, and interactive methods to build operational competencies. Assessment includes chapter tests and a final exam.
This "Learning by Doing" Java Programming course is designed for beginners, teaching core Java development skills and object-oriented thinking. It uses project-driven methods to cover practical software development processes, Eclipse IDE tools for coding and debugging, and basic testing and exception handling. The course emphasizes real-world applications and modern technologies, with assessment based on chapter tests.
This self-paced Linux System Administration course trains beginners to become junior Linux network administrators. It covers 10 core topics in two levels: foundational skills like OS installation, file/user management, and basic commands; followed by intermediate tasks including scripting, package management, process control, network configuration, and remote system access.
This introductory tea art course covers the fundamentals of Chinese tea culture, including the history, classification, and sensory evaluation of tea. Students learn practical brewing techniques for six major tea types, mastering skills from preparation to tasting. The curriculum also explores the aesthetic and philosophical aspects of tea, integrating Confucian, Buddhist, and Daoist influences. Emphasis is placed on developing both technical proficiency and creative artistry in tea presentation.
This course explores English-Chinese language contrasts through practical topics like word origins, naming customs, and translation of terms. It analyzes cross-cultural phenomena and modern word formation, enhancing learners' comparative understanding and language application skills in an accessible format.
This introductory course provides an overview of automation engineering, covering core concepts like control theory, system modeling, PID control, and modern strategies such as adaptive and fuzzy control. It explores practical implementation, including parameter detection and system development, while introducing emerging fields like IoT and digital factories. The course establishes a foundational understanding of automation's role in engineering, preparing students for advanced studies and professional applications.
This course, "Learning How to Learn," explores effective learning strategies based on neuroscience and cognitive psychology. It covers topics like memory enhancement, overcoming procrastination, efficient reading, and debunking learning myths. Designed for diverse learners, it provides practical steps to improve self-directed learning and academic performance.
This self-paced course, "Microscopic Chemical World," explores the origins of chemical activity in atoms and molecules by analyzing electron count, spatial distribution, and motion patterns. It connects these principles to the optical, electrical, and magnetic phenomena of the molecular world, emphasizing how foundational theories evolve with new experimental and physical insights while remaining relevant.
This course explores Wang Yangming's Mind Philosophy and its historical impact. It examines how his teachings address internal struggles ("bandits within the mind") and influenced modern Chinese reformers. The curriculum covers his life, the development of Mind Studies in East Asia, and its applications for self-awareness, relationships, and management. Designed as a cross-disciplinary general education course, it welcomes students and professionals interested in history, philosophy, and personal growth.
This course, "Military Theory," is a comprehensive program developed by leading military experts. It systematically covers five core areas: China's national defense, security, military thought, modern warfare, and information-based equipment across eight modules. Designed as an authoritative and up-to-date resource, it serves both as an essential university requirement and for self-study by those interested in national defense and military development.
This course covers essential material analysis techniques, focusing on X-ray diffraction and electron microscopy. It employs visual aids like graphics and animations to simplify complex concepts. Practical examples illustrate testing methods, making the content accessible. Recognized as a top course at Northeastern University, it is taught by experienced instructors.
This inorganic chemistry course covers core principles including energy changes in reactions, reaction direction/rate/equilibrium, acid-base/precipitation/redox reactions, atomic structure/periodicity, molecular/solid state properties, and coordination compound fundamentals. It provides foundational theoretical knowledge of chemical behavior and material characteristics.
Physical Chemistry (Part I) is a core course applying physics principles to solve chemical problems. It systematically covers thermodynamics, multi-component solutions, chemical equilibrium, and phase equilibrium. Taught by experienced instructors, it builds a solid foundation for students in chemistry, engineering, and related fields, enhancing analytical skills and scientific literacy.
Physical Chemistry (Part 2) systematically covers electrochemistry, chemical kinetics, surface/colloid chemistry, and statistical thermodynamics. This core course employs physics-based methods to address chemical problems, enhancing analytical skills and scientific literacy. It serves as a fundamental or review course for students in chemistry, engineering, and related fields.
This course introduces crowdfunding strategies for Chinese NGOs. It covers six modules: fundamentals of crowdfunding, long-term organizational preparation (branding, core values), practical project planning, proposal writing, post-launch promotion, and case studies of successful campaigns. The focus is on sustainable crowdfunding management beyond immediate fundraising techniques.
This course demystifies psychology by exploring its real-world applications, debunking common misconceptions. It covers key topics like memory, personality, emotions, and behavior using everyday language. The goal is to provide professional psychological insights, revealing a new perspective on daily life phenomena.
This course introduces the fundamentals of psychological counseling, focusing on practical conversation skills for daily life. It teaches how to apply counseling techniques to improve personal relationships and enhance life harmony, demystifying the process as an accessible art of communication rather than professional training.
This self-paced course offers an introduction to China's outstanding traditional culture, spanning its history, core characteristics, and fundamental spirit. It explores key concepts such as benevolence, integrity, and harmony, analyzing their timeless values and contemporary relevance through classical texts and practical examples. The course aims to foster a genuine understanding and appreciation of these enduring cultural principles.
This course introduces philosophy's essence as the pursuit of wisdom, exploring fundamental questions across Marxist, Western, and scientific philosophy. It highlights Nanjing University's century-old philosophy department, showcasing influential thinkers and their contributions. The course aims to clarify misconceptions, enhance philosophical literacy, and demonstrate the discipline's role in societal development.
This self-paced Computer Operating Systems course focuses on three key aspects: hardware-software co-design for OS module implementation, constructing large-scale software systems with trade-off analysis, and an engineering approach prioritizing concepts, techniques, and holistic problem-solving over pure theory and algorithms.
This course provides an overview of fundamental physics concepts—including mechanics, thermodynamics, electromagnetism, optics, and quantum physics—along with their scientific methods and modern applications. It explores how physics influences technology, society, and future developments, emphasizing critical thinking and interdisciplinary relevance. Designed for students across majors, it requires only basic math and encourages reflection on humanity's future through a scientific lens.
This course teaches fundamental English academic writing skills, focusing on the writing process and practical strategies like description, comparison, and argumentation. It aims to prepare students for university-level writing tasks, research papers, and study abroad applications through structured units and hands-on practice.
This self-paced Public Management course covers core concepts including government functions, public policy formulation, strategic management in public sectors, organizational leadership, and ethics. It equips learners with modern public management principles, operational mechanisms of public institutions, and analytical skills to address societal challenges. Proven through 16 years of graduate instruction and 12 years of government training, it develops practical problem-solving abilities for public sector contexts.
This self-paced E-Government course explores the core concepts, implementation processes, and key applications of digital governance. It is structured around four fundamental features: business reorganization, process reengineering, information sharing, and virtual organization. The curriculum aims to cultivate high-caliber professionals skilled in both emerging technologies and public administration, preparing them to advance modern governance systems.
This course focuses on campus safety and personal protection for university students. It addresses rising security issues, crime, and safety risks in higher education environments. The curriculum emphasizes essential safety knowledge, legal awareness, and preventive skills to enhance students' overall well-being and comprehensive development.
This course covers fire and explosion prevention in industrial enterprises. It analyzes high-risk processes in industries like petrochemicals, textiles, and food production, examining material properties, plant design, and operational safety. Students learn protection theories and techniques against fire, explosion, poisoning, and corrosion.
This course on Building Fire Safety focuses on foundational theories and practical skills in fire prevention and control. It integrates updated fire science, case studies, and hands-on training to enhance students' professional knowledge and operational abilities for real-world fire safety work.
This course provides comprehensive training in firefighting tactics, covering core theories, principles, and practical applications. Students learn command organization, operational actions, and tactical calculations to develop essential skills for analyzing and solving real-world fire rescue challenges, preparing them for leadership roles as fire squadron commanders.
"Fire Combustion Science" is a foundational course for fire command and rescue majors, covering 54 hours with a focus on core concepts, theories, and calculations of combustion. It builds essential knowledge for advanced safety and emergency response courses, supported by experienced faculty.
"Fire Emergency Rescue" is a technical and practical interdisciplinary course that provides theoretical guidance and technical support for firefighting teams. It covers chemical, traffic, and building collapse accidents, integrating knowledge from chemistry, physics, construction, equipment, tactics, and command. The course is essential for rescue operations and emergency response training.
This course provides a comprehensive overview of tuberculosis (TB), covering its history, epidemiology, and current challenges. It explores clinical aspects, diagnostics, drug resistance, treatment strategies, and the latest research, including molecular techniques and new therapies. Designed for healthcare professionals and students, it serves as both an introduction and an update on TB management and public health efforts.
This required course for nursing master's students covers key research steps: formulating questions, literature review, study design, data collection, proposal and thesis writing. Through 36 hours of case-based teaching, it focuses on practical challenges, developing students' ability to identify problems and apply research methods. Highly rated (96-99), it effectively guides thesis development.
This graduate-level pathophysiology course focuses on disease etiology, compensatory mechanisms, and pathogenesis. It emphasizes mastering key concepts through clinical cases and common pathological processes, aiming to develop students' analytical and problem-solving skills. Assessment covers specified core content only.
This course, "Exploring MOOCs," offers a comprehensive analysis of MOOCs through videos and lectures by Professor Li Xiaoming. It covers theoretical concepts in the first three weeks and a practical guide to creating MOOC videos in the final week. Designed for educators and administrators, it includes discussions, peer reviews, quizzes, and a hands-on video production task to demystify MOOC implementation and development.
This elective course explores folk literature along the southern Silk Road. It covers myths, legends, folktales, the "Hua'er" folk songs, and proverbs from multiple ethnic groups, analyzing their evolution and cultural symbols within this historical regional context.
This elective course explores folk literature along the southern Silk Road. It covers foundational knowledge, multi-ethnic myths, their symbolic evolution, local legends, folktales, the "Hua'er" folk songs, and proverbs. The focus is on the cultural heritage and narrative traditions of diverse ethnic groups in this historic region.
This course explores decorative patterns, tracing their evolution from ancient pottery to modern design. It covers pattern functions, classifications, artistic features, and cultural significance. Students learn creation methods—from sketching to composition—and apply design principles. Suitable for art students and enthusiasts, it builds foundational skills in pattern design and aesthetic appreciation.
This introductory microeconomics course explores how markets address resource scarcity through individual choices and coordination. It covers core principles like supply-demand mechanisms and market failure corrections, serving as a foundational bridge between high school and university-level economics. The course includes optional credit certification through China's Advanced Placement program.
This self-paced AP Biology prep course focuses on cellular structure, function, and the chemistry driving biochemical reactions. It features expert instructional videos, AP-style practice questions with detailed solution guides, and prepares students for the corresponding exam topics.
This self-paced AP Biology exam prep course focuses on genetics, exploring mechanisms of genetic information transfer across generations at molecular and organismal levels. It covers how DNA governs life processes, featuring expert instructional videos, AP-style practice questions, and guided problem-solving tutorials to prepare students for the exam.
This self-paced AP Biology exam prep course focuses on evolution and diversity. It covers how evolutionary processes drive genetic change, shape biodiversity, and unify life. The course includes expert instructional videos, AP-style practice questions, and guided problem-solving to prepare students for the exam.
This AP Biology exam prep course focuses on ecology, covering interactions among organisms and their environment. It includes expert instructional videos, practice questions, and problem-solving guidance to prepare students for the AP exam. Key topics include populations, communities, ecosystems, and biological systems.
This AP Environmental Science exam prep course (Part 1) focuses on the living world. Over six weeks, it covers introductory topics, ecosystems, evolution, biodiversity, biomes, and aquatic systems, including weekly labs. Featuring expert instruction and AP-style practice questions, it prepares students for the exam.
This course prepares students for the AP Environmental Science exam, focusing on population dynamics, sustainability, and land/water use. It features expert instructional videos, AP-style practice questions, and guided problem-solving to build exam proficiency.
This self-paced AP Environmental Science prep course focuses on pollution and Earth's resources. It covers major pollution issues, resource availability, and their impacts on the planet and humanity. Featuring expert instructional videos, AP-style practice questions, and guided problem-solving, it prepares students for the corresponding exam topics.
This introductory immunology course explores how the human body defends against pathogens. It covers core concepts of innate and adaptive immunity, focusing on cellular interactions, signaling, and pathogen recognition. Designed for health professionals and biomedical researchers, it establishes foundational terminology to understand clinical literature and uses analogies to clarify complex topics. This is Part I of a two-part series.
This second part of the immunology course focuses on T cell function and the coordination of immune responses. It explores how the body defends against pathogens, covering adaptive immunity, cellular interactions, signaling, and pathogen recognition. Designed for health professionals and researchers, it introduces key concepts and terminology to understand clinical literature, using analogies to explain complex topics.
This course explores the transformative impact of digital technology on medicine and healthcare. It examines key areas like social media, wearable tech, big data, and personalized medicine, analyzing their effects on doctor-patient roles and the healthcare ecosystem. Participants will learn to critically assess opportunities, challenges, and the future of digital health.
This introductory electromagnetism course covers core topics including electric and magnetic fields, Gauss's law, circuits, and Faraday's law. Designed as a standard second-semester physics course, it requires calculus and introductory mechanics as prerequisites. The 12-week format features video lectures, assignments, design projects, and exams, with an estimated 10-12 hours of weekly study.
This self-paced course explores the connections between religion and hip-hop culture over six weeks. It examines how hip-hop addresses fundamental life questions through rap music's history, religious themes, and artists' spiritual expressions. Using multimedia resources, the course analyzes hip-hop as a lens for understanding religious identity and meaning, suitable for beginners.
This self-paced introductory psychology course covers core topics including historical development, research methods, cognitive processes, and social development. It provides foundational knowledge through structured modules, helping beginners understand key psychological concepts and practical applications for self-awareness. The concise content offers a comprehensive overview of the discipline's scientific framework and real-world relevance.
This introductory psychology course covers core topics including historical development, research methods, cognitive processes, and social development. It provides foundational knowledge through four key perspectives: history, methodology, thematic studies, and practical applications. Designed for beginners, the course helps students systematically understand psychological principles while exploring real-world applications for self-awareness and personal growth.
This online course, "Medical Pharmacology (Spring 2019)," serves as a digital supplement to in-person pharmacology classes. It focuses on the history of drug discovery and the clinical application of common medications. Bridging clinical and basic medical sciences, it is essential for both medical and pharmacy students.
This course explores traditional Chinese ethnic handicrafts like weaving, embroidery, and intangible cultural heritage techniques (e.g., Tujia brocade). It focuses on learning core skills and innovatively integrating them into modern life, aiming to preserve cultural heritage and showcase its beauty in contemporary society.
This self-paced Computer Networks course covers fundamental concepts, protocols (TCP/IP), and the OSI model layers, with emphasis on network layer routing protocols. It combines theoretical knowledge with practical skills in network programming, packet analysis, and device configuration for routers and switches.
This 2018 fall Data Structures course covers fundamental data organization (logical and storage structures) and algorithm design/evaluation. Students explore core structures like lists, stacks, queues, trees, and graphs, along with essential algorithms for searching and sorting. The course emphasizes applying these concepts to solve practical engineering problems, blending strong theoretical foundations with hands-on practice. Assessment is based entirely on assignments, with a passing score of 60.
This self-paced Data Structures course covers logical and storage structures, algorithm design, and evaluation. Students explore linear lists, stacks, queues, trees, graphs, and fundamental algorithms like searching and sorting. Emphasis is placed on applying these concepts to solve engineering problems. The course is both theoretical and practical, with grading based entirely on assignments and a 60% passing score.
This course introduces fundamental computer concepts including system architecture, data representation, hardware/software, operating systems, office software, programming, databases, multimedia, networks, web design, and cybersecurity. It aims to build essential computer literacy and problem-solving skills for practical applications in various academic fields.
Calculus I is an undergraduate course covering single-variable calculus fundamentals, including functions, limits, continuity, derivatives, and integrals with their applications. It emphasizes theoretical understanding and problem-solving skills, taught in English to enhance both mathematical proficiency and language ability.
This course introduces AI fundamentals for beginners, covering China's AI development and applications. Students will learn key concepts like data, algorithms, and computing power, explore neural networks (CNN, RNN), and understand core principles such as F(X)=Y, gradient descent, and machine learning types (supervised, unsupervised, reinforcement). Practical examples and analogies are used to demystify AI concepts.
This Computer-Aided Design (CAD) course teaches engineering drawing and modeling for chemical, energy, pharmaceutical, and light industries. Students learn AutoCAD software, parametric drawing, and Excel macro programming for solving engineering equations and optimization. The course aims to enhance practical design skills and efficiency through CAD tools and secondary development.
This course on Corporate Strategic Management (Spring 2019) focuses on developing and sustaining competitive advantage through effective strategy formulation, implementation, and control. It integrates global perspectives with China-specific contexts, using dynamic environmental analysis. Students learn to assess internal/external factors, make strategic choices, and enhance implementation via governance, structure, and culture.
This course explores sustainable development as humanity's key challenge, focusing on how economic growth can be socially inclusive and environmentally sustainable. It examines interactions between the economy, finite resources, climate change, and social equality, providing an overview based on social, policy, and physical sciences.
This course explores sustainable urban development challenges posed by rapid urbanization. It examines how cities can adapt through innovative technologies, energy systems, and transportation to support future population growth while meeting 21st-century sustainability goals.
This course explores the science of climate change and international negotiations to address it. It examines the causes and impacts of global warming, the critical 1-2°C target, and strategies for mitigating greenhouse gas emissions. The focus is on developing and applying practical solutions within different national frameworks.
This course explores early childhood development's critical role in sustainable development. It examines brain development, nutrition, and effective care programs through neuroscience, sociology, and anthropology. Led by experts from Harvard, NYU, and UNICEF, it provides scientific insights into how early years shape lifelong well-being.
This course explores the "Planetary Boundaries" framework, examining the Earth's ecological limits and human impacts. It covers global environmental trends, the Anthropocene concept, and challenges like unsustainable consumption. The focus is on understanding planetary resilience and strategies for achieving sustainable, equitable development within Earth's safe operating space.
This course explores the challenges and opportunities of rapid urbanization, focusing on sustainable development. It addresses urban issues like poverty, infrastructure deficits, and inequality, while examining solutions for inclusive, resilient, and productive cities. The goal is to understand pathways for achieving Sustainable Development Goal 11 by 2030.
This course explores the 17 Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), a global agenda adopted in 2015 for long-term planetary and societal health. It covers key social, economic, and environmental targets through 2030, emphasizing our shared responsibility for sustainable stewardship across all nations and levels of society.
This course, "University Chinese: Appreciation of Pre-Qin to Tang Literature," is a national-level quality program led by Professor Wang Bugao. It features a structured curriculum with 64 sessions, supported by authoritative textbooks and online resources. Designed to enhance students' native language proficiency, it combines lectures by Professor Wang and other experts, offering flexible credit options for universities.
This course, "University Chinese (Part 1)," is a nationally acclaimed program led by Professor Wang Bugao. It covers Chinese language and literature, utilizing award-winning textbooks and resources. Designed to enhance students' native language proficiency, it offers flexible credit options and features lectures by experienced professors, serving as a model for university Chinese education nationwide.
This course, "University Chinese (Part 2)" in self-paced mode, is a national top-quality resource-sharing course led by Professor Wang Bugao. It focuses on enhancing college students' native language proficiency through 64 lessons aligned with nationally planned textbooks. The curriculum covers Chinese language and literature, featuring lectures by Professor Wang and other experts, and supports flexible credit options for universities.
"Drug Analysis" is a core course for pharmacy majors, covering essential theories and practices in pharmaceutical quality control. It integrates modern sciences and plays a key role in drug development and production. The course includes both theoretical and practical components, with assessments based on chapter tests (80%) and final exams (20%). It is vital for graduate admissions and national pharmacist licensing.
This course teaches Android-based smart device application development. It covers core topics like UI programming, Activity lifecycle, Intent communication, data storage, services, and networking. Designed for students and professionals with Java basics, it uses videos, quizzes, and exams to equip learners with skills for developing, testing, and deploying mobile apps.
This self-paced course introduces interaction design concepts, history, and foundational knowledge. It covers design principles, user research, and methods for creating optimal user experiences. Students learn practical skills in information architecture, prototyping, testing, and iterative interface design, applying these through real-world projects.
This course focuses on the installation and debugging of electrical control systems, integrating key topics such as motors, PLCs, inverters, power electronics, and automation. It employs a task-driven, six-step teaching method to develop practical skills through hands-on projects, fostering professional competencies in electrical automation for equipment manufacturing.
This course uses Omron CP1E PLCs in a project-based, task-driven format. It covers six projects with 21 practical tasks, integrating theory and hands-on skills. Students learn PLC system design, installation, and debugging through a complete workflow process, while developing professional competencies in a learn-by-doing environment.
This core undergraduate course in Petroleum Engineering covers essential drilling and completion technologies, including well design, drilling fluids, bit selection, well control, trajectory control, cementing, and reservoir protection. It integrates foundational theory with practical applications and modern industry practices, emphasizing problem-solving skills through hands-on training and engineering design.
This course "Campus Psychology: Supporting Every Student's Growth" focuses on applying psychological principles to foster students' mental well-being. It covers foundational theories, strategies for maintaining mental health, identifying and correcting psychological and behavioral issues, and designing group training programs. The goal is to enhance students' overall quality and address challenges like anxiety and learning difficulties.
This course focuses on electrical control system installation and debugging, integrating theory and practice from motor control, PLC, frequency converters, power electronics, and automation systems. It employs a task-driven, six-step teaching method to develop professional skills through hands-on training. Assessment is based on assignments (40%) and a final exam (60%).
This course cultivates students' ideological, moral, and legal foundations. Guided by Marxism and Chinese socialist theories, it addresses key issues in students' development. The core is to instill correct values, ethics, and legal awareness, fostering well-rounded socialist builders with ideals, integrity, and a sense of responsibility.
This course introduces the fundamentals of innovation and entrepreneurship. It covers developing an innovative mindset, mastering creative thinking techniques, and learning practical innovation methods. Students will explore the entrepreneurial process, from idea generation and team building to writing business plans and managing new ventures, aiming to enhance overall innovation and entrepreneurial capabilities.
This course focuses on PLC application technology using Omron CP1E PLC as an example. It is structured around six project-based tasks, integrating theory with hands-on practice. Students learn through a complete workflow process—planning, implementation, and evaluation—to develop skills in PLC system design, installation, and debugging, while building professional competence.
This core course for Building Environment and Energy Engineering majors covers heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) technologies. It focuses on calculating building loads, designing HVAC systems, and selecting equipment to control indoor thermal, humidity, and air quality environments. The course also introduces energy efficiency, system testing, and emerging industry advancements.
This self-paced course explores the rich heritage of Bashu culture in Sichuan, China. It covers ancient origins, key historical sites like the Dujiangyan irrigation system and Sanxingdui ruins, and cultural highlights such as Sichuan opera. The course examines how this regional culture evolved within Chinese civilization, showcasing its unique contributions and enduring legacy.
"Mechanical Principles" is a core technical foundation course for mechanical engineering majors. It focuses on the common theories and design methods of machines and mechanisms. Key topics include structural analysis, kinematic methods, dynamics, and the design of common mechanisms like gears, cams, and linkages. The course aims to develop students' abilities in mechanical system innovation, comprehensive design, and engineering practice.
This course, "Innovation and Entrepreneurship in the Intelligent Era," explores how to integrate AI and smart technologies into entrepreneurial ventures. It focuses on developing a five-layer entrepreneurial competency model, covering self-awareness, innovation, technical skills, business acumen, and teamwork. The curriculum emphasizes fostering innovation capabilities and applying technologies like computational thinking and machine learning across industries, supported by practical project guidance.
This "Soil Mechanics" course covers fundamental concepts, principles, and methods, integrating engineering applications and recent advancements. Key topics include soil properties, stress and effective stress, permeability, compression and consolidation, shear strength, soil compaction, earth pressure, slope stability, and foundation bearing capacity. It is a practical and foundational course designed for undergraduate students in civil and hydraulic engineering.
This self-paced course provides a comprehensive overview of women's health and human rights across the lifespan. It examines critical, life-and-death issues shaped by gender discrimination, inequality, and violence—including poverty, education, reproductive health, HIV/AIDS, and work. The MOOC fosters an international learning community through interactive discussions and encourages applying knowledge to real-world community contexts.
This course explores the core concept of "Great Unification" (大一统) in Chinese cultural history. It examines key historical transitions—from the Shang-Zhou to Zhou-Qin, Tang-Song, and Yuan-Qing periods—to address how and why China maintained political and cultural unity. The course highlights how this tradition evolved into a modern framework under the Communist Party, emphasizing cultural confidence, national unity, and the rejuvenation of Chinese civilization.
This course explores the essence of Chinese business philosophy and entrepreneurial spirit, rooted in Confucian merchant traditions. Through case studies and comparative analysis, it highlights people-centered values as the core of Chinese commerce, examining its historical evolution and modern relevance for corporate culture and management. It emphasizes adapting these principles to foster contemporary entrepreneurship and healthy government-business relations.
This course examines the Communist Party of China's role in national rejuvenation through historical and comparative analysis. It explores the Party's founding, its path to governance, and its leadership in China's development, emphasizing why socialism with Chinese characteristics is essential for the country's progress.
This course covers principles and methods of landscape plant design, focusing on plant germplasm resources, ecological concepts, and technical applications. It includes urban park planning, road greening, and specialized garden design. Emphasizing practical case studies and current trends, it integrates theory with real-world engineering practices for sustainable landscape solutions.
This logistics management course introduces core concepts like carriers, freight forwarders, and logistics companies. It covers supply chain topics such as the bullwhip effect and supplier evaluation through practical interviews. Using cases like the Belt and Road Initiative, it explains practical knowledge including HS code classification and cargo inspection, with brief insights into customs procedures.
This course, "STEM Curriculum Design and Case Studies," is a pioneering MOOC introducing systematic STEM education design. It covers fundamental STEM theories, teaching methodologies, and practical case analyses using engaging multimedia. Participants learn to utilize global STEM tools and resources for curriculum development. Designed for undergraduates, graduates, and educators, assessment includes assignments (40%) and a final exam (60%).
This course teaches effective scientific paper writing, covering structure, publication ethics, and promotion strategies. Led by Tsinghua scholars and Elsevier publishers, it provides practical guidance on organizing content and navigating academic publishing to enhance research impact.
This student-led computer vision course bridges the gap between theory and practice for beginners. Through eight biweekly lectures, it covers AI fundamentals, machine learning, neural networks, and key CV tasks like classification and detection. The program concludes with a hands-on challenge to apply learned skills.
This course features recorded thesis defenses from Tsinghua University's 2017 doctoral and master's graduates across various disciplines. Shared as a MOOC, it aims to provide academic resources, foster scholarly exchange, and demonstrate the university's commitment to research quality and open educational content.
This course introduces the fundamental concepts, properties, classification, and geological origins of gemstones and jade. It covers their physical and optical characteristics, conventional identification methods, and factors influencing their value. The curriculum also explores over 20 varieties of crystalline gems, 10+ types of jade, and several organic gemstones, detailing their specific features, geological occurrences, sources, and related cultural histories.
This self-paced course introduces gemology fundamentals, covering basic concepts, properties, classification, and geological origins of gemstones. It explores their physical and optical characteristics, conventional identification methods, and factors influencing quality and value. The curriculum details over 20 crystalline gem varieties (e.g., diamond, ruby), 10+ polycrystalline jades (e.g., jadeite, nephrite), and several organic gems (e.g., amber, coral), including their features, geological occurrences, origins, and
This course introduces mechanics through engaging experiments and hands-on projects. It covers science TV program production, interactive game design, and practical CAD skills. Students learn to create 10 original devices using laser cutting technology, progressing from basic to advanced designs.
This course cultivates makers through three core modules: analyzing science TV segment props and experiments, designing engaging science games, and teaching basic AutoCAD for laser-cutting 10 original mechanical devices from simple to complex. It focuses on hands-on mechanics experiments and creative fabrication.
This course presents China's perspective on global climate change, covering scientific understanding, national challenges, and regional impacts. It explores adaptation and mitigation measures, detailing China's policies, its INDC, and the synergies between climate action, energy security, environmental protection, and sustainable development. Launched around COP21, it highlights China's ambitious climate commitments.
This course introduces fundamental accounting principles, covering core theories, rules, and methods. It focuses on financial accounting, including key concepts, bookkeeping, accounting standards, financial statement preparation, and ratio analysis. Students will learn to interpret financial data, analyze business performance, and understand related areas like auditing and internal controls. The course provides a foundation for further studies in accounting.
This introductory business course explores the commercial world through ten key concepts, examining industries, companies, and individuals. It covers business fundamentals like strategy, leadership, and innovation, explaining enterprise creation, growth, and management. Designed for beginners, it builds a logical framework for understanding how businesses and society operate.
This course combines theory and case studies, with entrepreneurs sharing practical methods and experiences alongside professor commentary. It aims to spark students' interest in entrepreneurship, cultivate key entrepreneurial qualities, and teach essential skills such as opportunity identification, venture design, and operational management. Students will learn to analyze and solve problems across various startup stages.
This introductory course explores the "Zizhi Tongjian," a monumental 11th-century Chinese chronicle covering 1,362 years of history. It examines the text's political and military narratives, focusing on its insights into governance, leadership, and historical patterns. The course aims to make this classic accessible, highlighting its enduring wisdom for personal and societal development.
This course offers an introductory guide to "Zizhi Tongjian," a monumental Chinese chronicle compiled by Sima Guang. It explores the text's political and military narratives spanning over 1,300 years, emphasizing its historical insights and practical wisdom on governance and personal development. Designed as a humanities course, it makes this classic accessible, highlighting its enduring relevance and cultural value.
This course explores the rise and fall of the Tang Dynasty through the lens of the "Zizhi Tongjian," a classic Chinese historical text. It analyzes key figures and events from the Sui, Tang, and Five Dynasties periods, extracting practical wisdom on governance, self-cultivation, and family ethics. The focus is on understanding historical context and applying traditional insights to modern life.
This self-paced course, "The Rise and Fall of the Tang Dynasty," explores the Sui, Tang, and Five Dynasties period through the lens of Sima Guang's *Zizhi Tongjian*. Guided by Professor Zhang Guogang, it analyzes key historical figures and events to extract practical wisdom on governance, self-cultivation, and family ethics. The course provides a clear historical framework and demonstrates methods for drawing insights from classical Chinese texts.
This course explores traditional Chinese literati aesthetics, focusing on the "Four Arts of Life": flower arranging, tea brewing, incense, and painting. It delves into their historical roots and philosophical significance, promoting a harmonious, refined lifestyle. Through expert lectures and interactive sessions, students engage with practices like gardening, tea appreciation, incense rituals, and makeup artistry, blending cultural heritage with modern living.
This course explores traditional Chinese lifestyle arts, focusing on the "Four Arts of Life": flower arranging, tea brewing, incense appreciation, and painting display. It delves into their historical roots and modern practice as pathways to cultivate elegance, harmony with nature, and personal refinement. Featuring expert guests, the curriculum extends to related topics like gardening, fragrance, and etiquette, offering an interactive guide to a mindful and aesthetic way of living.
This course explores the art of modern living aesthetics through flower arrangement. It covers the historical development and cultural characteristics of Eastern and Western floral traditions, integrating practical skills in plant knowledge, color composition, and design techniques. Participants learn to create expressive floral art while cultivating mindfulness, elegance, and harmony with nature.
This course explores modern living aesthetics through traditional Chinese literati arts. Part One focuses on flower arrangement (Ikebana), covering its history across Eastern and Western cultures, plant knowledge, color theory, and hands-on techniques. It emphasizes mindfulness, connecting with nature, and cultivating an elegant lifestyle. Part Two expands to tea ceremony, incense, etiquette, and wellness, featuring interactive sessions with industry experts.
This course, "The Journey of Aesthetics," explores the evolution of aesthetic consciousness across historical eras. It examines how societal spirits—from primitive and slave societies through feudal, capitalist, and socialist systems—shape and transform artistic expression, revealing the dialectical laws of their development.
This course explores Confucian self-cultivation as a practical philosophy for daily life, focusing on texts like "The Great Learning" and "The Doctrine of the Mean." It integrates traditional teachings with modern psychology and traditional Chinese medicine to address contemporary spiritual and emotional challenges. The curriculum emphasizes personal development, moral growth, and social contribution, aiming to build character and wisdom through practical application.
This introductory logic course for non-majors focuses on the study of valid reasoning forms. It covers key topics including propositional and predicate calculus, deductive and inductive reasoning, and a brief history of logic. The course emphasizes fundamental logical principles and methods rather than just content, aiming to develop students' analytical thinking skills.
This introductory logic course for non-majors focuses on the study of valid reasoning forms. It covers key topics including propositional and predicate calculus, deductive and inductive reasoning, and a brief history of logic. The course emphasizes fundamental logical principles, methods for evaluating and constructing arguments, and an overview of classical and non-classical systems.
This course explores the foundational aspects of ancient Chinese ritual civilization. It examines the historical development of rites and music culture, a core element of Confucianism, through key texts like the "Three Ritual Classics." The curriculum aims to build a framework for understanding traditional etiquette, enhance cultural literacy, and guide the practical application of these principles in modern life.
This course explores the core of traditional Chinese culture through ancient rites and civilization. It examines the evolution of ritual systems from the Zhou Dynasty, their development by Confucian scholars, and their codification in classical texts. The content highlights their profound influence on Chinese history, governance, and the broader East Asian cultural sphere.
This course explores cultural China through 4-6 sets of premium artifacts, highlighting key archaeological discoveries in fields like shipbuilding and jade. It traces academic research on Chinese civilization, offering a comprehensive and engaging introduction to ancient China's achievements and evolving historical understanding.
This course explores cultural China through 4-6 sets of premium artifacts, using archaeological discoveries in fields like shipbuilding and jade to trace the evolution of Chinese civilization. It presents cutting-edge research, offering students a comprehensive and vivid understanding of ancient China's achievements.
This self-paced course offers an introduction to Kunqu Opera, a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage and a pinnacle of Chinese traditional theater. It covers fundamental knowledge including its history, artistic features, roles, music, language, and current status. The course aims to cultivate appreciation and understanding of Kunqu, guiding learners on how to enjoy this classical art form.
This course focuses on appreciating ten classic Kunqu operas, including "The Peony Pavilion" and "The Palace of Eternal Youth," along with twenty selected scenes. It covers each work's author, plot, characters, performance highlights, role types, artistic features, and common versions to enhance audience understanding and enjoyment.
This course focuses on appreciating classic Kunqu opera works, including ten full-length plays like "The Peony Pavilion" and "The Palace of Eternal Life," along with twenty selected scenes. It introduces each work's original author, plot summary, main characters, performance highlights, role types, artistic features, and common versions to enhance viewing appreciation.
This undergraduate course explores the origins of Western philosophical spirit through ancient Greek and Roman thought. It examines core themes like rationality, ontology, epistemology, and ethics, aiming to cultivate theoretical thinking and enhance humanistic qualities. The curriculum covers key philosophers and concepts, tracing the development of philosophical inquiry from its foundations.
This course explores the origins of Western philosophical spirit through ancient Greek and Roman thought. It examines core themes like rationality, ontology, epistemology, logic, ethics, and science, aiming to develop students' theoretical thinking and humanistic qualities by analyzing key philosophers and their enduring intellectual legacy.
This course, "Appreciation of Tang and Song Ci Poetry," systematically explores representative works, authors, and key genres of Tang and Song dynasty ci poetry. It emphasizes literary analysis while covering historical and cultural contexts, aiming to enhance students' critical reading and appreciation skills. Led by Professor Wang Bugao, an expert in the field, it is a popular offering at Tsinghua and Southeast Universities.
This self-paced course, led by Professor Wang Bugao, offers a systematic exploration of Tang and Song dynasty ci poetry. It covers key poets, representative works, major schools, and historical context, aiming to enhance students' appreciation and critical analysis of classical Chinese poetry.
This national elite course, "Immortal Art: Exploring Masters and Classics," systematically examines the development and characteristics of Chinese and Western art history. It compares classic artworks, integrating art history, aesthetic theory, and cultural studies. The course emphasizes contrasts between East and West, tradition and modernity, aiming to enhance students' aesthetic judgment, appreciation, and cultivate well-rounded professionals with humanistic sensibilities.
This course, "Immortal Art: Exploring Masters and Classics," offers a comparative analysis of Chinese and Western art history. It examines key artworks, aesthetic theories, and cultural contexts, focusing on contrasts between East and West, tradition and modernity. Through studying artists from ancient times to modern figures like Van Gogh and Warhol, the course aims to enhance students' aesthetic judgment, appreciation, and cultivate a humanistic perspective.
This course provides an introduction to the origins, evolution, and current state of the U.S. political system. It examines the constitutional framework, mechanisms of checks and balances, and historical shifts in political power. The curriculum explores avenues for political participation, analyzes evolving political culture, and evaluates policy outputs to assess the overall condition of American democracy.
This course explores football's scientific principles and societal impact. It covers technical skills, tactical strategies, biomechanics, physiology, injury prevention, and psychological aspects. Students analyze match videos to understand rules, training methods, and modern trends, fostering both physical engagement and a deeper appreciation of the sport's cultural significance.
This self-paced course, "Football and Science," explores the sport's fundamentals, scientific principles, and societal impact. It covers football techniques, tactics, physical and physiological aspects, rules, and development trends. Through video analysis and instruction, students gain a comprehensive understanding of football's scientific foundations and cultural significance, fostering both practical knowledge and a deeper appreciation for the game.
This introductory C++ programming course covers object-oriented programming fundamentals, including classes, objects, data structures, and algorithms. It follows the C++11 standard and is designed for beginners, with no prior programming experience required. The curriculum progresses from basic syntax to advanced topics like inheritance and polymorphism, using a practical teaching approach.
This introductory C++ programming course, offered since 1999, teaches object-oriented programming (OOP) fundamentals. It covers C++ syntax, core data structures, and algorithms, emphasizing how OOP encapsulates data and methods into classes and objects for modular, secure, and reusable software development. The curriculum is designed for beginners, integrating practical problem-solving with essential programming concepts.
This advanced C++ programming course introduces object-oriented programming (OOP) using C++. It covers core OOP concepts like classes, objects, encapsulation, inheritance, and polymorphism, alongside fundamental data structures and algorithms. Designed for beginners, the course emphasizes practical problem-solving, applying OOP principles to ensure modular, secure, and reusable code. It serves as a comprehensive foundation in both C++ syntax and modern software development methodologies.
This advanced C++ programming course introduces object-oriented design, emphasizing encapsulation, classes, inheritance, and polymorphism. It covers essential data structures, algorithms, and modern C++11 standards, providing a comprehensive foundation for software development with practical applications and a focus on code reusability and maintainability.
This course introduces object-oriented and visual programming using Visual C++, focusing on Windows programming fundamentals. It covers essential concepts like event-driven message response, geometric drawing, text I/O, keyboard/mouse handling, and MFC basics. Through practical examples and detailed code, students learn to develop applications with controls, resource files, and document interfaces, including database programming techniques.
This course introduces object-oriented and visual programming using Visual C++ and MFC. It focuses on Windows programming fundamentals, MFC library basics, and event-driven message response mechanisms. Key topics include graphics, text I/O, keyboard/mouse handling, controls, document interfaces, and database programming, taught through practical examples and case studies.
This introductory Java programming course covers fundamental syntax, object-oriented concepts, and GUI development basics. Topics include classes, methods, inheritance, polymorphism, I/O streams, collections, and graphical interfaces. Designed for beginners, it requires no prerequisites but assumes basic programming knowledge is helpful.
This self-paced Java programming course covers fundamental syntax and object-oriented design principles. It introduces I/O stream libraries, collection frameworks, and basic GUI development methods for building foundational Java applications.
This course introduces green building concepts, global development histories, and evaluation systems. It analyzes how climate-appropriate technologies, rather than costly high-tech solutions, define sustainable design. Through international case studies, it compares regional strategies and emphasizes the necessity of developing green buildings suited to China's specific conditions.
This course explores the essence, origins, evolution, and future of universities through a comparative study of Eastern and Western educational cultures. It examines how universities have adapted over centuries, their role in society, and the impact of digital learning. Students reflect on their identity within the academic community and the enduring mission of higher education.
This self-paced course explores the essence, origins, evolution, and future of universities through a historical and cultural lens. It examines how universities have shaped learning, community, and societal roles across centuries, blending Eastern and Western educational perspectives. The course encourages reflection on one's identity and responsibilities as part of the global academic community.
This Tsinghua University elective course, "Entrepreneurship Guidance: Face-to-Face with Masters," introduces students to startup fundamentals. Through direct interactions with successful entrepreneurs and investors, it covers key topics like venture capital insights, product design, branding, and company culture. Aimed at undergraduates, graduates, and early-stage founders, the course inspires and educates future innovators.
This course guides university students in career exploration and decision-making. It covers self-assessment, job search skills, and adapting to change, helping students balance ideals with reality and define their career paths. It emphasizes that career choice is a continuous process of personal growth and life planning.
This self-paced course guides university students in career exploration and decision-making. It covers self-assessment, job search strategies, and adapting to change, helping learners balance ideals with reality while defining personal and professional goals. Essential for career planning and development.
This introductory materials science course provides a comprehensive overview of the field. It systematically explores various material systems—including metals, ceramics, polymers, and composites—covering their structure, properties, production, and applications. The course highlights historical context, current advancements, and future trends, presenting key concepts accessibly to equip students with a foundational understanding of the discipline's scope and research methodologies.
This introductory course on tumor biology covers fundamental concepts, biological mechanisms, and clinical aspects of cancer. Using authoritative textbooks like "The Biology of Cancer," it combines theoretical knowledge with clinical insights. Designed for both undergraduate and graduate students, the course is taught by professors and clinical experts, making complex topics accessible to learners from various scientific backgrounds.
This course, "Calculus: Limit Theory and Single-Variable Functions," covers foundational topics including real numbers, functions, limit theory, differentiation, and integration of single-variable functions. It emphasizes key concepts such as the completeness of real numbers and the fundamental ideas of definite integrals, serving as an essential prerequisite for further studies in science and engineering disciplines.
This course, Calculus B(1), is a foundational mathematics course designed primarily for science and engineering majors. It covers essential topics including real numbers, functions, limit theory, differential calculus, and integral calculus for single-variable functions. The curriculum emphasizes key concepts such as continuity, derivatives, applications of derivatives, indefinite and definite integrals, with a focus on the fundamental ideas and techniques of integration.
This course covers multivariable calculus and multiple integrals, including differentiation and integration of multivariable functions, their applications, line and surface integrals, and ordinary differential equations. Designed for STEM majors, it serves as a foundational requirement for advanced studies in science and engineering.
This course covers core topics in multivariable calculus, including differentiation and integration of multivariable functions, multiple integrals, line and surface integrals, and ordinary differential equations. Designed primarily for STEM majors, it serves as a fundamental prerequisite for advanced studies in science, engineering, and related fields.
This introductory linear algebra course covers fundamental concepts including solving linear equations via Gaussian elimination, matrix operations/decompositions, vector spaces, eigenvalues/diagonalization, and least squares methods. It emphasizes both theoretical foundations and practical applications in science and engineering, while developing mathematical reasoning and proficiency with English technical terminology.
This introductory linear algebra course covers core concepts including solving linear systems via Gaussian elimination, matrix operations/decompositions, vector spaces, eigenvalues/diagonalization, and least squares methods. It emphasizes both theoretical foundations and practical applications in science and engineering, while building mathematical reasoning skills and English technical terminology proficiency.
This advanced linear algebra course builds upon foundational concepts, covering positive definite matrices, similarity transformations (Jordan form), singular value decomposition, linear transformations, generalized inverses, and complex matrices. It emphasizes the integration of theory with practical applications in engineering, geometry, and economics, aiming to develop mathematical logic and abstract thinking skills while strengthening proficiency in solving linear systems and matrix operations.
This course, "University Physics I (Mechanics and Thermodynamics)," covers foundational physics principles through mechanics and thermodynamics. It employs logical explanations, demonstrations, and problem-solving methods to teach core concepts. Designed with segmented video lessons, it categorizes content by difficulty to accommodate diverse learner backgrounds, emphasizing the integration of fundamental ideas.
This course, "University Physics 2," covers electromagnetism, wave optics, and introductory quantum physics. It builds on mechanics and thermodynamics from Physics 1, focusing on fundamental concepts in each area. Optics includes interference, diffraction, and polarization, while quantum physics introduces basic principles and their applications to atomic and nuclear structure. The content is structured into core and optional advanced sections.
This introductory mechanics course for physics majors covers Newton's laws, motion theorems, continuum mechanics, vibrations, waves, and special relativity. It emphasizes fundamental principles and methods to build a strong foundation in physics, fostering analytical and research skills essential for further scientific study.
This introductory course covers fundamental and cutting-edge topics in modern biology. It explores biological principles across molecular, cellular, organismal, and ecosystem levels, including genetics, evolution, and ecology. The course emphasizes current research in areas like genomics and molecular medicine, integrates interdisciplinary approaches, and highlights experimental design to foster critical thinking in the life sciences.
This introductory General Biology course (Spring 2019) provides a foundational overview of life sciences. It covers core principles across molecular, cellular, and organismal levels, divided into two main sections: Cell & Molecular Biology and Plant & Animal Biology. The curriculum explores fundamental topics like cell structure, genetics, metabolism, organismal form and function, and basic evolutionary concepts, integrating modern research to build a comprehensive framework for further biological studies.
This course cultivates ideological and moral character with a legal foundation. Guided by Marxism and socialist theories, it integrates traditional Chinese culture and global insights. It addresses students' ethical and legal challenges, fostering worldview, values, and legal awareness. The goal is to enhance students' moral and legal qualities, preparing them as well-rounded socialist contributors.
This course, "Ideological and Moral Cultivation and Legal Basis," is a foundational political theory class for university students. It integrates ideological, political, and practical education, guided by Marxism-Leninism and socialist theories. The core content focuses on developing students' worldview, values, and legal awareness, addressing moral and legal challenges in personal development to cultivate well-rounded socialist builders.
This course outlines China's modern history from 1840, covering resistance against foreign invasion, the quest for national independence, liberation, and socialist modernization. It combines online lectures, multimedia materials, and discussions to explore how China chose Marxism, the Communist Party, socialism, and reform, fostering historical awareness and understanding of national conditions.
This course outlines China's modern history from 1840, covering the struggles against foreign invasion, the quest for national independence, and the path to socialism and reform. It combines online lectures, multimedia materials, and discussions to foster historical awareness and deepen understanding of China's development and ideological choices.
This course introduces Mao Zedong Thought and the theoretical system of socialism with Chinese characteristics. It covers topics like the Sinicization of Marxism, socialist reform, and the overall layout of socialism with Chinese characteristics. The course employs an interactive teaching model to transform students from passive listeners into active learners, emphasizing the integration of knowledge with practice to foster confidence in China's development path.
This course introduces Mao Zedong Thought and the theoretical system of socialism with Chinese characteristics. It covers topics like the Sinicization of Marxism, socialist reform, and China's development path. Using an interactive teaching model, it encourages active learning through discussion, writing, and practice, aiming to deepen students' understanding and confidence in socialism with Chinese characteristics.
This course systematically introduces Marxism's origins, core theoretical features, and its philosophical, political-economic, and scientific socialist foundations. It aims to equip students with a comprehensive understanding of Marxist principles, perspectives, and methodology, fostering a correct worldview. Utilizing a blended online-offline teaching model, it emphasizes active learning through comparison, discussion, and critical thinking.
This course features lectures by a lead professor sharing academic growth and research insights, aiming to inspire students' sense of responsibility and pursuit of science and truth. It includes classic readings, group discussions, and writing exercises to enhance knowledge in science, humanities, arts, and engineering, while improving communication, critical thinking, and academic writing skills.
This course examines the transition from ancient to modern societies through foundational philosophical principles. It explores how ancient thought established duty-based order, while the Enlightenment introduced rights-based frameworks centered on individual freedom. Key themes include the shift from collective duty to individual rights, legitimacy of governance, and the role of ideas in shaping social structures.
This course explores the transition from ancient to modern societies through the lens of Western thought. It examines how ancient principles like duty and collective priority shaped classical societies, and how the Enlightenment introduced modern concepts such as individual rights and freedom. Key themes include the philosophical foundations of social order and the shift from duty-based to rights-based frameworks.
This Tsinghua University core humanities course surveys the history of global decorative arts and crafts, tracing their evolution as a vital record of human civilization. It examines countless artifacts from across the world, analyzing them as key carriers of cultural heritage. The study is framed as essential for cultivating cultural literacy and enhancing comprehensive education within the humanities.
This Tsinghua University humanities course surveys the history of global decorative arts and crafts, spanning millions of years. It examines artifacts as vital carriers of human civilization, exploring their evolution across different cultures. The study is framed as essential for cultivating cultural literacy, enhancing comprehensive education, and strengthening the humanities discipline.
This course bridges art and daily life, moving beyond traditional art history and practice. It encourages critical thinking through analyzing artworks and hands-on creation, aiming to make art accessible and meaningful for personal growth and societal enrichment.
This self-paced course, "Inspiration of Art," bridges the gap between art and daily life. It moves beyond traditional art history and practice, focusing on how art nurtures individuals like sunlight and air. Students develop critical thinking by analyzing artworks and engaging in creative projects, using art to explore emotions, foster innovation, and achieve inner harmony—ultimately integrating art into life itself.
Engineering Graphics (Spring 2019) is a core technical foundation course at Tsinghua University. It focuses on fundamental principles of engineering design representation, covering projection theory, drafting standards, 2D/3D modeling, and multi-view drawings. The course develops spatial imagination and technical communication skills through hand sketching, instrument drawing, and computer-aided design.
This self-paced Engineering Drawing course from Tsinghua University teaches fundamental skills in technical design representation. It covers projection theory, drafting standards, 2D/3D modeling, and engineering documentation. The course develops spatial visualization and design thinking through hand sketching, instrument drawing, and computer-aided techniques.
This course introduces the fundamentals of engineering thermodynamics, covering core concepts, the first and second laws, properties and processes of ideal gases, and gas power cycles. It serves as a key foundation for energy, mechanical, and aerospace engineering, focusing on energy conversion and efficient thermal utilization.
This course covers advanced engineering thermodynamics, focusing on real working fluid properties, steam and refrigeration cycles, moist air, thermodynamic differential relations, and fundamentals of chemical thermodynamics. It serves as a key foundation for energy, mechanical, and aerospace engineering disciplines.
This course teaches effective scientific paper writing and publication strategies. It covers structure, journal standards, ethics, and promotion techniques, featuring Tsinghua scholars and Elsevier publishers. Students gain practical skills for drafting, submitting, and disseminating research papers while adhering to academic integrity.
This course explores the theory and practice of Public-Private Partnerships (PPP), focusing on China's policy context and operational models like BOT and TOT. It covers core topics including policy, risk management, and economic evaluation through expert lectures. The goal is to deepen understanding of PPP concepts, frameworks, and current trends.
This course introduces Petri nets, covering their models, theory, and applications. It systematically presents hierarchical net systems—from basic to colored nets—defining their structures, dynamics, and analysis methods. Key concepts include concurrency, conflict, and synchronization. Theoretical focus is on synchronization theory and information flow systems. Applications address classic problems like dining philosophers and business process management. The course encourages critical thinking by linking Petri nets to traditional models and questioning established knowledge.
This course introduces traditional Chinese landscape painting techniques. It covers aesthetic principles, brushwork, materials, and specific methods like hemp-fiber, ox-hair, and axe-cut texture strokes, along with tree trunk, leaf dotting, and branch techniques.
This course provides a systematic introduction to the core principles and spirit of the 19th National Congress of the Communist Party of China. It covers ten key areas, including the congress theme, historic achievements, socialism with Chinese characteristics entering a new era, and Xi Jinping Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era. Designed for Tsinghua students and a broader audience, assessment is based on chapter quizzes from video lectures.
This course explores Xi Jinping Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era, focusing on the people-centered new development philosophy. It systematically covers five core concepts: innovation, coordination, green development, openness, and sharing. The 12-hour curriculum helps students understand the connotation and practice of socialist modernization, deepening their comprehension of China's development path.
This course provides a practical introduction to WeChat Mini Program development. It covers fundamental concepts, framework structure, data binding, modularization, caching, components, APIs, and full-stack application skills. Through hands-on projects, learners will master essential development techniques and launch their own mini programs.
This course introduces fundamental botanical concepts, classification systems, and identification methods for common flowers. Students learn to appreciate and recognize various floral groups, including spring-blooming Rosaceae species, famous ornamental flowers, succulents, and aromatic plants, through thematic lessons.
This course introduces the core principles of microeconomics, focusing on individual decision-making, market coordination, and resource allocation. It explores how rational choices, competition, and entrepreneurship drive innovation and economic growth. Key topics include market-government boundaries, the impact of government intervention, and the benefits of globalization. Designed to provide a foundational understanding, it equips students to analyze real-world economic phenomena and participate effectively in economic activities.
Pathology is a foundational medical discipline that investigates diseases primarily from a morphological perspective. By examining structural changes in diseased tissues and integrating functional and metabolic alterations, it elucidates fundamental mechanisms of disease development and reveals their underlying nature, serving as a crucial guide for clinical diagnosis.
This course introduces industrial production management for STEM students, covering system design, process optimization, and operational strategies. Topics include production planning, quality control, inventory management, lean manufacturing, and supply chain management. It builds foundational management skills for future engineering careers.
This course offers an in-depth exploration of 49 scenic views across 23 classical gardens from the Ming Dynasty, a period often overshadowed by later Qing-era remnants. It uniquely analyzes their design, aesthetics, and historical narratives through the lens of form and spatial dynamics, presenting groundbreaking research in an engaging manner. This is the first season of the "Ming Garden Appreciation" series.
This introductory Electrical Engineering course for non-majors covers fundamental circuit theory, analysis methods, and simulation tools (Spice/Multisim). It explores electric motors, relay-contactor controls, and Programmable Logic Controllers (PLC), focusing on practical applications for various engineering disciplines.
This course covers fundamental circuit principles, including linear/nonlinear resistor circuits, time-domain analysis of dynamic circuits, and steady-state analysis under sinusoidal excitation. It provides essential knowledge for electrical engineering majors, integrating basic methods, modern components, and practical applications. Prerequisite math and physics reviews are included for accessibility.
This course introduces Japanese language fundamentals (lessons 1-9, covering pronunciation, basic grammar, and verb conjugation) while exploring Japanese culture and its significant influence on China. It analyzes social phenomena to compare Japanese and Chinese societal traits, emphasizing that understanding culture is crucial for effective communication. The 12-unit course blends 80% in-person and 20% online instruction, taught by different instructors for language and culture components.
This self-paced course introduces Japanese language and culture, focusing on basic Japanese phonetics, grammar, and key cultural insights. It explores how Japanese culture influences Chinese youth and compares societal traits between China and Japan. The curriculum covers lessons 1-9 of the textbook, enabling foundational self-study, with 20% online and 80% offline engagement.
This course builds on Japanese language foundations by integrating cultural analysis, examining how Japanese society influences Chinese youth values and identity. It contrasts Japanese "island-nation traits" with Chinese "mainland agrarian traditions" to decode modern bilateral tensions. Emphasis is placed on understanding cultural nuances as essential for effective communication beyond mere language proficiency.
This course introduces assembly language programming as a foundational computer systems course. It covers X86 and MIPS assembly, instruction sets, data representation, and the interaction between hardware and software. Emphasizing its role as a bridge, it helps students connect program execution with computer operations, fostering a deep understanding of system-level thinking.
This introductory course on analog electronic technology covers semiconductor fundamentals, amplifier circuits, operational amplifiers, frequency response, feedback systems, signal processing, waveform generation, power amplifiers, and DC power supplies. It equips students with essential knowledge and skills in analyzing and designing analog electronic systems, serving as a foundation for further studies in electrical and information engineering.
This course covers fundamental analog electronic technology applications, focusing on signal processing, waveform generation, power amplification, DC power supplies, and circuit analysis. It provides essential knowledge and skills in designing and analyzing analog circuits, serving as a foundation for further studies in electronics and related fields.
This introductory course covers fundamental digital electronics, including logic algebra, gate circuits, combinational and sequential logic design, pulse waveform generation, semiconductor memory, programmable logic devices, and A/D & D/A conversion. It emphasizes basic theories, analytical skills, and practical applications to build a solid foundation for advanced electronic studies.
This course introduces ARM Cortex-M microcontroller and embedded systems, focusing on practical applications. Designed for undergraduates with C programming basics, it covers development methods and encourages hands-on innovation for tech competitions. Using 32-bit microcontrollers as examples, it enables students to quickly implement projects and participate in activities like smart car races.
Theoretical Mechanics is a foundational engineering course covering kinematics, statics, and dynamics. It employs both vector mechanics (based on Newton's laws) and analytical mechanics (based on variational principles). The course includes core topics like particle and rigid body motion, equilibrium, and dynamical systems, supplemented with engaging lectures, demonstrations, and practical competitions to enhance learning.
"Engineering Materials" is a foundational technical course for mechanical and manufacturing majors. It covers the relationship between material composition, processing, structure, and properties, introducing metals, polymers, ceramics, composites, and functional materials. The course focuses on failure analysis, material selection principles for mechanical components, and practical application, equipping students with the ability to choose appropriate materials and plan processing routes based on engineering requirements.
This course introduces the fundamental phenomena and laws of electromagnetic interactions at the macroscopic scale. As a core theoretical physics subject, it focuses on applying field theory and solving partial differential equations to understand electromagnetism, which underlies most physical phenomena. Essential for advanced physics and engineering studies, it is renowned for its challenging integration of mathematics and physics.
This advanced electrodynamics course explores electromagnetic interactions as fundamental forces governing phenomena from atomic to macroscopic scales. It focuses on solving partial differential equations using field theory, integrating mathematical rigor with physical principles. Essential for advanced physics and engineering studies, it covers core macroscopic electromagnetic phenomena and their broad scientific applications.
This self-paced "Quantum Mechanics (Part 1)" course introduces the fundamental principles and concepts of quantum mechanics, the theoretical foundation of modern physics and technology. It covers core theories and methods for describing the microscopic world, analyzing experimental phenomena and key concepts through reasoning and derivation. The content is divided into basic and advanced modules, suitable for both physics majors and non-specialists.
This self-paced course covers advanced quantum mechanics principles, exploring fundamental concepts and their applications in modern physics and technology. It addresses both core topics and extended materials, using analytical methods to interpret quantum phenomena and develop problem-solving skills for understanding the microscopic world.
This Organic Chemistry course (Spring 2019) provides a systematic introduction to the nomenclature, structures, physical/chemical properties, and synthesis of major compound classes (e.g., alkanes, alkenes, aromatics, carbonyls). It focuses on fundamental reaction mechanisms—substitution, addition, elimination, rearrangement, redox—and explores stereochemistry, structure-reactivity relationships, and methods for structure determination.
This self-paced organic chemistry course systematically covers the nomenclature, structures, physical/chemical properties, synthesis, and applications of key compound classes (alkanes, alkenes, alkynes, aromatics, alcohols, carbonyls, amines, etc.). It emphasizes fundamental reaction mechanisms (substitution, addition, elimination, rearrangement, redox), stereochemistry, structure-reactivity relationships, and methods for structure elucidation.
This course focuses on college student mental health, covering self-awareness, emotional regulation, stress management, interpersonal skills, and life values. It aims to promote self-acceptance, social adaptation, and personal growth through practical topics like confidence building and relationship management.
This introductory computer literacy course provides a foundational understanding of core computing principles and IT trends. It focuses on developing computational thinking and information literacy, exploring the cultural impact of technology through real-world cases. The content is dynamically updated with insights from industry experts, aiming to equip students from all disciplines with a macro perspective on the evolving digital era.
This course focuses on C++ programming within the Linux environment. It covers core C++ concepts, object-oriented and generic programming, and integrates them with Linux system programming topics like processes, threads, memory management, and networking. The goal is to develop abstract and computational thinking, transforming theoretical knowledge into practical skills for system-level development.
This self-paced Soil Mechanics course covers three core modules: theoretical principles (soil permeability, deformation, strength), practical applications in engineering problems, and hands-on laboratory experiments. It develops analytical thinking, engineering judgment, and technical skills for civil and hydraulic engineering.
Hydraulics is a technical foundation course for water conservancy, civil engineering, environment, and related fields. It studies fluid motion laws and fluid-boundary interactions, focusing on water. The course covers fundamental theories, specialized topics like flow dynamics, and practical experiments, aiming to develop analytical skills and problem-solving abilities in engineering hydraulics.
This course covers unsaturated and saturated groundwater in aquifers, applying hydrological cycle and water balance principles. It focuses on storage, movement, and transformation processes, teaching modern observation, simulation, and prediction techniques using software like HYDRUS and FEFLOW/MODFLOW. The course provides foundational knowledge for water resource development and ecological protection.
This course introduces fundamental principles of optical engineering, covering applied optics (ideal systems, ray tracing, imaging quality) and physical optics (electromagnetic theory, interference, diffraction, crystal optics, Fourier optics). It provides essential knowledge for photonics and instrumentation majors, emphasizing both theoretical foundations and practical applications.
This self-paced course on Combustion Theory provides a semester-long introduction over twelve lectures. It covers scientific fundamentals like thermochemistry, mass transfer, and chemical kinetics, followed by modeling of practical combustion systems. Topics include laminar premixed/non-premixed flames, droplet and solid fuel combustion, and an introduction to turbulent combustion, using key reactor models and simplified governing equations.
This course explains automotive engine principles in two parts. The first covers overall performance, fuel economy, working cycles, and engine-vehicle matching. The second focuses on combustion processes, emissions formation, control methods, and alternative fuels. It consistently compares gasoline and diesel engines to clarify working principles.
This course focuses on fundamental 2D expression skills in automotive styling design. It covers essential topics such as vehicle proportions, perspective, light and shadow, material representation, and drawing techniques. Through systematic instruction and practice, learners develop foundational hand-sketching abilities for car design, emphasizing both theoretical knowledge and practical training.
This introductory course outlines the seven-layer knowledge framework of Electronic Information Science and Technology, covering fields from electromagnetism to media and cognition. It provides a comprehensive overview of the discipline's core concepts and their interconnections, designed for students and professionals to gain foundational insights into the subject's structure and key principles.
This course covers fundamental data structures, their design principles, and implementation techniques. It focuses on building efficient algorithms and analyzing their performance, extending from basic concepts to recent research findings.
This course focuses on the design, implementation, and principles of various data structures, extending from fundamental concepts to recent research. It emphasizes algorithm design and performance analysis, equipping students with key techniques to build efficient algorithms—a core component in computer science.
This foundational computer science course uses C/C++ to teach core programming concepts and computational thinking. It covers basic syntax, data structures, algorithms (sorting, recursion, etc.), and file operations. Emphasizing problem-solving and hands-on practice, it aims to develop practical coding skills and establish a solid base for advanced studies.
This course covers core concepts and implementation techniques of operating systems, using mainstream OS examples and the ucore teaching OS for practical experiments. It focuses on resource management, system software principles, and provides foundational knowledge for OS development and application software design.
This advanced Java programming course delves into core topics including multithreading, network programming, JVM architecture, garbage collection, collections framework, reflection, proxies, and bytecode technology. It builds upon foundational skills to provide a deeper understanding of Java for developing robust applications, particularly in distributed systems and big data contexts.
This course builds on programming fundamentals, using C++ to enhance abstract thinking and master object-oriented design. It covers core syntax, interface design, the open-closed principle, and data-operation separation. Topics include interface-based programming, generic programming, and the C++ Standard Template Library, targeting learners with prior programming experience.
This course provides a comprehensive introduction to MEMS and microsystems, covering fundamental theories, design analysis, microfabrication techniques, and key devices. It explores core topics including sensors, actuators, RF MEMS, optical MEMS, and BioMEMS/microfluidics. Emphasis is placed on integrating design with manufacturing, combining foundational knowledge with cutting-edge research and industrial applications.
This course covers fundamental micro/nanofabrication techniques including oxidation, deposition, lithography, etching, and 3D printing. It explains principles through animations and equipment demonstrations, preparing students for device fabrication in research. The course also introduces MEMS, integrated circuits, and current industry trends.
This self-paced course covers nuclear radiation physics and detection, forming a complete system from radiation generation to detection. It emphasizes nuclear decay, reactions, and radiation-matter interactions, while training students in understanding nuclear data like decay schemes. The course also details three primary radiation detectors (gas, scintillation, semiconductor), focusing on signal formation, operational parameters, and statistical fluctuations. Students will master fundamental nuclear physics principles and detection methods.
This course introduces the fundamentals of social science research methods. It covers key steps including selecting research topics, designing studies, and collecting data through both qualitative and quantitative approaches. Students will learn to develop a research proposal and cultivate a rigorous scientific mindset for evaluating social research.
This "Life English Listening & Speaking" course focuses on practical communication skills through eight daily life topics. Featuring authentic dialogues from diverse native and Chinese speakers, it enhances listening comprehension and conversational ability via real-world scenarios, vocabulary building, and interactive exercises.
This "Life English Listening and Speaking" course enhances practical communication skills through eight daily life topics. Featuring authentic dialogues from diverse international speakers, it covers introductions, family, food, learning, holidays, hobbies, emotions, and health. Each unit includes vocabulary explanations, cultural insights, and exercises to improve conversational fluency in real-world contexts.
This course introduces the core principles of communication studies, exploring the nature and patterns of human communication. It systematically analyzes communication phenomena, covering the description of communication activities, analysis of relationships, behavioral norms, and problem-solving. As an interdisciplinary field intersecting with sociology and psychology, it focuses on both theoretical foundations and practical applications.
This self-paced course explores the principles of communication, examining its nature, patterns, and systematic knowledge. It covers describing communication activities, analyzing relationships, defining behaviors, and addressing challenges. As an interdisciplinary field intersecting sociology and psychology, it focuses on applied, independent study of human interaction.
This introductory psychology course covers 13 core topics including consciousness, perception, memory, emotion, personality, and social behavior. It employs empirical research and classic theories to provide foundational knowledge, correct misconceptions, and teach basic research methods in psychology. The focus is on positive psychology and scientific thinking in the field.
This introductory psychology course covers 13 key topics including consciousness, perception, memory, emotion, personality, and social behavior. It employs empirical research and classic theories to provide foundational knowledge, correct misconceptions, and teach basic research methods in psychology. The focus is on positive psychology and understanding psychological thinking.
This course offers an introduction to Chinese meticulous figure painting, combining art appreciation and hands-on creation. Students will study historical masterpieces, learn traditional techniques like line drawing and coloring, and follow the complete creative process from sketching to composition. Designed for undergraduates, graduates, and enthusiasts, it aims to enhance artistic skills and cultural understanding across disciplines.
This course explores visual language by deconstructing art into abstract components, moving beyond traditional aesthetics. It encourages students to develop personal, contemporary definitions of art and establish their own visual systems. Participants will gain new insights into the fundamentals of visual art, requiring basic art history knowledge and an interest in exploring creative possibilities.
This course explores 7,000 years of Chinese clothing history, examining its evolution, cultural significance, and aesthetic trends through archaeological artifacts and visual materials. It analyzes traditional styles, craftsmanship, and design elements, while demonstrating their successful adaptation into modern fashion. The course bridges historical study with contemporary design application.
This course explores 7,000 years of Chinese clothing history, examining its evolution, cultural significance, and aesthetic trends through artifacts and expert insights. It analyzes traditional styles, craftsmanship, and techniques for transforming historical elements into modern fashion design, bridging historical knowledge with contemporary creative application.
This course, Medical Parasitology, focuses on parasitic diseases prevalent in tropical and subtropical regions, particularly in developing countries. It covers the study of medically relevant parasites, including protozoa, helminths, and arthropods, examining their biology, life cycles, and interactions with hosts. The curriculum also addresses disease mechanisms, clinical symptoms, diagnosis, treatment, and prevention strategies, serving as a bridge between foundational science and clinical application.
This course offers an introductory exploration of medicine, covering topics from environmental health to molecular disease mechanisms. Designed for medical students and interested learners, it features insights from both research and clinical experts. The goal is to foster interest in medicine, impart foundational knowledge, and promote healthy lifestyles for personal and community well-being.
This introductory medical course explores the relationship between health and disease from both macro environmental and micro molecular perspectives. Designed for medical students and interested learners, it covers disease mechanisms, prevention, and management through insights from research and clinical experts. The goal is to foster medical knowledge, promote healthy lifestyles, and enable basic health guidance.
This self-paced Software Engineering course covers fundamental concepts, principles, and methods across the software lifecycle, including development management, requirements modeling, design implementation, and testing maintenance. It emphasizes core principles like testability, software architecture, modularity, and reusability, while addressing system complexity and iterative development. The course focuses on problem-solving skills and practical training to cultivate professional software engineering habits and foundational competencies.
This course introduces core theoretical computer science concepts, including formal languages, automata (finite automata, pushdown automata, Turing machines), grammars, decidability, and computational complexity (P, NP). It covers properties of regular and context-free languages, the Pumping Lemma, and explores fundamental questions in computation.
This course introduces Tsinghua University's 8-year Medical Scientist Training Program, which integrates clinical medicine with modern life sciences like immunology and neuroscience. It explains how the university cultivates physician-scientists who excel in both patient care and transformative biomedical research.
This course, "The Mysteries of Medicine," outlines Tsinghua University's unique 3+2+3 eight-year program for training physician-scientists. It explores how the university integrates its comprehensive strengths to develop clinicians with both exceptional bedside skills and advanced research capabilities in fields like immunology, neuroscience, and stem cell biology. The program emphasizes translational medicine, aiming to cultivate future leaders who innovate at the intersection of clinical practice and scientific discovery.
This course introduces fundamental geology and engineering geology, covering Earth's evolution, rocks/minerals, geological processes, structures, and maps. It also addresses groundwater, geotechnical properties of soils/rocks, and analysis methods for engineering geological issues, providing essential knowledge for civil and geological engineering applications.
This course, "Air Pollution Control Engineering," covers the sources, impacts, dispersion, and control technologies of air pollution. It focuses on fundamental principles, control processes for major pollutants, calculation methods, and recent research advances. Designed to develop problem-solving skills, it prepares students for engineering design, research, and management in air pollution control.
This course covers the sources, impacts, and control technologies of air pollution, focusing on fundamental principles, pollutant treatment processes, and engineering calculations. It aims to develop students' abilities to analyze and solve air pollution control problems, integrating the latest research and practical applications.
This course focuses on biological treatment technologies in water and wastewater engineering. It covers aerobic and anaerobic processes, biological nutrient removal, natural treatment systems, and sludge management. Students learn fundamental principles, design calculations, operational features, and the latest research advancements in the field.
This course introduces key physicochemical water treatment technologies, including coagulation, sedimentation, filtration, disinfection, membrane separation, and adsorption. It covers fundamental principles, process design, equipment operation, and recent research advances for both water and wastewater treatment applications.
This foundational course introduces measurement and detection technology, covering sensor mechanisms, signal processing, and data analysis. Students learn to construct testing systems, understand signal transmission, and apply methods for accurate physical quantity measurement. Essential for instrumentation and mechanical engineering majors.
This course covers optoelectronic instrument design principles, including design methodologies, error theory, and key components like standards and alignment systems. It explores overall design through microscopes, interferometers, and spectrometers, while discussing industry trends and practical experiments in optical measurement and imaging techniques.
This course covers fundamental theories and engineering applications of fluid machinery, including turbines, pumps, fans, and valves. Topics include classification, working principles, energy conversion, performance curves, multiphase flow analysis, and operational characteristics. It integrates engineering practices with the latest research, using multimedia and case studies for an engaging learning experience.
This course introduces the fundamental components and typical structures of automotive chassis systems. It covers the functions, structural features, and working principles of the transmission, suspension, steering, and braking systems. The course aims to develop students' ability to analyze chassis systems and key components, providing a foundation for further studies and professional work. Content is updated to include emerging new energy vehicle chassis technologies.
This core Industrial Engineering course covers production planning and control essentials, including operations strategy, demand forecasting, inventory management, aggregate planning, MRP, scheduling, lean production, and theory of constraints. It equips students with skills to optimize manufacturing systems and enhance industrial efficiency.
This core industrial engineering course covers production planning and control essentials, including operations strategy, demand forecasting, inventory management, aggregate planning, MRP, scheduling, lean production, and theory of constraints. It equips professionals with skills to optimize manufacturing systems and enhance operational efficiency.
This course introduces classical control theory, covering system modeling, analysis, and design. Key topics include feedback principles, transfer functions, stability, time/frequency responses, and PID controllers. It serves as a foundational course for engineering control systems, emphasizing both theoretical principles and practical applications.
This course, "Automatic Control Theory (2)," is a core follow-up to foundational control theory, focusing on modern control systems. It covers state-space analysis, including controllability, observability, stability, and system synthesis methods like pole placement and optimal control. Designed for engineering students, it builds theoretical foundations for designing complex automated systems.
This course explores common sensor types, covering their principles, implementation methods, applications, and the latest research and product developments. It focuses on how sensors detect and convert measured signals into usable outputs.
This course focuses on transistor- and circuit-level analysis and design of digital integrated circuits, primarily using CMOS technology. It covers CMOS inverters, combinational and sequential logic circuits, arithmetic units, interconnect modeling, and parasitic effects. Emphasis is placed on optimizing circuit structures for area, speed, and power, while introducing standard design methodologies and workflows.
This course introduces financial engineering fundamentals, covering three core areas: neoclassical asset pricing models (CAPM, arbitrage-free pricing, factor models), derivative pricing methods using binomial trees and no-arbitrage principles, and structured financial product design for corporate risk management and financing. Case studies illustrate practical applications in business contexts.
This course trains students in essential photography skills and visual storytelling for journalism. It covers technical fundamentals and news image sensitivity, preparing aspiring journalists to meet industry standards. Additional discussions explore photography's evolving role in digital media environments.
This introductory course in film and television production teaches camera operation, editing systems, visual composition, and audiovisual language. Students learn to create various video formats, including news reports, documentaries, and short films. Through workshops and project analysis, they gain hands-on experience and are encouraged to submit their work for awards.
This introductory course on interface design provides beginners with a comprehensive overview of the field's current state, applications, and trends. It focuses on GUI and H5 web design, guiding students through a complete design process to build foundational knowledge and practical skills for future learning.
This course explores the interactions between buildings and their environments, covering indoor thermal, air quality, acoustic, and lighting conditions, as well as outdoor microclimates. It examines how these factors impact human health and comfort from physiological and psychological perspectives. Students learn to assess environmental needs, analyze influencing factors, and apply principles for creating and controlling optimal built environments.
This self-paced HVAC course covers heating, ventilation, and air conditioning systems, integrating their core concepts, components, and working principles. It focuses on building climate and air quality control, analyzing equipment characteristics, application suitability, and development trends. Through case studies, students learn to apply diverse technical solutions to solve practical engineering problems.
This foundational course covers core web front-end development skills, including HTML, CSS, JavaScript, jQuery, ES6, and Node.js. It provides essential knowledge and practical resources for beginners in front-end programming.
This self-paced Combinatorics course introduces fundamental discrete mathematics concepts essential for computer science. Covering basic counting principles, generating functions, recurrence relations, the Pigeonhole Principle, inclusion-exclusion, and Polya's counting theorem, it explores enumeration methods for discrete structures. Designed for learners with elementary math knowledge, the course demonstrates how combinatorial theory underpins computational advancements.
This graduate-level course covers core big data platform technologies, including distributed system architecture, programming, stream processing, data storage, and in-memory computing. It focuses on design principles, technical depth, and practical solutions for distributed data challenges, preparing students for advanced research and development in the field.
This course guides students in writing international journal and conference papers, covering academic conventions, cultural differences, proper citation, and participation in scholarly activities like conferences and editorial roles. It also briefly addresses selecting research topics and applying for grants.
This course offers a series of practical lectures on big data science and applications for both IT and non-IT students. It focuses on integrating theoretical methods with real-world case studies, covering platforms, modules, and tools. The goal is to inspire innovation and equip students with the skills to solve practical problems using big data technologies.
"Founding New Ventures" is a practical entrepreneurship course co-hosted by Tsinghua University. It combines lectures with real-world incubation, offering selected student teams mentorship, investor networking, and access to a dedicated incubation fund. The course focuses on addressing startup challenges and providing essential resources, featuring pitch evaluations by investors and experts to help teams launch and grow their businesses.
This self-paced Engineering Ethics course addresses the growing global demand for ethical training in engineering. It covers professional ethics and practical decision-making in engineering, aligning with international standards like the Washington Accord. Designed for Chinese engineers in global contexts, it emphasizes real-world application to cultivate ethical awareness, responsibility, and decision-making skills for complex engineering challenges.
This course, "Engineering Ethics (Spring 2019)," focuses on the practical application of ethical principles in engineering. It covers professional ethics and ethical decision-making in real-world engineering contexts, aligning with international standards like the Washington Accord. The course aims to cultivate ethical awareness, responsibility, and decision-making skills in engineers to address complex challenges in global and Chinese engineering practices.
This course introduces engineering ethics, focusing on professional moral issues in engineering. It aims to develop ethical awareness and analytical skills among engineering graduate students. Covering both theoretical foundations and practical applications, the course addresses ethical decision-making in real-world engineering contexts, preparing engineers for global challenges and cross-cultural professional standards.
This introductory course provides an overview of data science, covering fundamental concepts in data mining and big data. It explores technical methods, legal frameworks, and practical applications, aiming to establish a foundational understanding and mindset for the field.
This introductory course provides foundational knowledge in data science, covering core concepts in data mining and big data. It explores technical methods, legal frameworks, and practical applications, aiming to cultivate essential data-driven thinking through an engaging teaching approach.
This introductory course in education provides graduate students with foundational concepts, principles, and research methods in the field. It explores the nature of education, outlines how to conduct educational research, and discusses the essential qualities required for professionals in education.
This course introduces fundamental big data systems, covering tools, platforms, and development methods. It explores cloud computing, file storage, computing frameworks, in-memory computing, NoSQL, and stream data processing. Students learn to apply and develop big data solutions while gaining a theoretical foundation for advanced studies.
This course introduces fundamental big data systems, covering tools, platforms, and development methods. It explores key topics like cloud computing, file storage, computing frameworks, in-memory computing, NoSQL, and stream data processing. Students will learn practical applications and underlying principles to build a solid foundation for advanced big data studies.
This course explores how big data revolutionizes urban planning, focusing on data acquisition, analysis, and visualization techniques. It covers applications in urban systems and planning design, using China's urban development as a case study. Students will learn to utilize new data and quantitative methods for urban research and planning.
This self-paced course on Finite Element Analysis and Applications introduces the finite element method as a computational tool for solving complex engineering and scientific problems. It covers fundamental theory, including elasticity, numerical discretization, and solution principles, alongside practical implementation using software like ANSYS and MATLAB. The course emphasizes physical concepts and real-world applications through examples, making it essential for mechanical, aerospace, and civil engineering students.
This course, "Automotive Theory," is a core module for vehicle engineering students and professionals. It employs dynamics methods to evaluate automotive performance, establishing relationships between performance metrics and structural parameters. Key topics include power performance, fuel economy, braking, handling stability, and ride comfort, focusing on assessment, influencing factors, and improvement strategies.
This course introduces the inner product transform principle for analyzing dynamic signals from operating machinery. It teaches how to extract useful information to monitor internal conditions, identify issues, and predict potential failures. The method unifies various signal analysis techniques, such as Fourier series and wavelet transforms, by comparing signals with specific functions, simplifying complex mathematical relationships and enhancing practical application.
This course covers dynamic signal analysis for monitoring machinery operation. It focuses on inner product transformation principles to extract state information from random, time-varying signals. Key topics include Fourier series, Fourier transform, and wavelet transform as unified methods for signal comparison and fault diagnosis.
This course explores human-centered design principles, integrating ergonomics and cultural factors into product development. It covers user research, task analysis, interface evaluation, cross-cultural design, and emerging topics like human-robot interaction. Through case studies and research insights, it equips learners with analytical skills to assess and enhance user experience effectively.
This course introduces computational geometry, focusing on algorithmic design and analysis for discrete geometric structures. Key topics include convex hulls, Voronoi diagrams, Delaunay triangulations, and geometric queries. It covers strategies like incremental construction, plane sweep, and divide-and-conquer, providing a geometric perspective for problem-solving in research.
This course introduces fundamental theories and methods of machine learning for big data, covering statistical learning principles, core machine learning techniques, and deep learning approaches. It aims to equip senior undergraduates and graduate students with the ability to apply these methods to solve practical problems.
This self-paced course on Linear System Theory covers fundamental concepts in control science and engineering. It focuses on time-domain and frequency-domain analysis, including state-space modeling, system structure, feedback control, and transfer function matrices. The course emphasizes rigorous logic training and innovative thinking for solving engineering problems.
This advanced chemical thermodynamics course builds on four fundamental postulates to derive classical thermodynamic laws. It covers equilibrium, stability, phase and chemical equilibria, thermodynamic property calculations for pure substances and mixtures, and applications to modern chemical, materials, and bioengineering systems.
This course introduces social statistical analysis using R. It covers exploratory data analysis, inferential statistics, and advanced methods like regression, focusing on applying statistical reasoning to social science research. Practical examples from sociology and psychology are used to teach data interpretation and evidence-based conclusions.
This course introduces social statistical analysis using R, covering exploratory data analysis, inferential statistics, and advanced methods like regression. It emphasizes logical thinking over computation, applying statistical principles to social science research with practical examples.
This introductory law course compiles inaugural lectures by Tsinghua professors, covering core disciplines like constitutional law, jurisprudence, civil law, and international law. It presents essential legal principles, research methodologies, and critical thinking skills to guide students into advanced legal studies.
This course explores visual communication design thinking and methodologies. It aims to break mental constraints, compare Eastern and Western design philosophies, and develop analytical and creative problem-solving skills. Key topics include rational vs. intuitive thinking, systematic design approaches, and interdisciplinary methods, supported by theories and practical exercises.
This course explores refined residential design, focusing on its evolution in China, common interior design errors, and methods to enhance comfort and functionality. It covers layout optimization, human-centric community planning, and international design inspirations. Participants will gain practical theories and techniques for creating elevated living spaces that balance artistry with everyday needs.
This course explores refined residential design in China, covering its development stages, common interior design errors, and methods to enhance comfort and practicality. It addresses layout optimization, human-centric community planning, and insights from international practices. Participants will gain theoretical knowledge and practical skills for creating detailed, livable homes.
This course introduces DeST software for simulating indoor thermal environments in buildings. It covers using simulation tools for HVAC system design, building energy efficiency evaluation, and research applications.
This course explores aging-adaptive residential space and environmental design in China's aging society. It covers aging demographics, elderly care policies, industry trends, and international best practices. Participants learn to create senior-friendly facilities, communities, and home modifications through planning and architectural approaches. Suitable for designers, care professionals, and families, it equips learners with practical principles to enhance living environments for the elderly.
This course explores aging-adaptive residential space and environmental design in China's aging society. It covers aging trends, elderly care policies, industry developments, and international best practices. Participants will learn practical planning, architectural design, and home modification methods to create safe, comfortable living environments for older adults. Suitable for designers, care professionals, and families.
This course explores the history of Chinese architecture from prehistoric times to the Song, Liao, and Jin dynasties. It covers the evolution of major cities, palace complexes, religious structures (temples and pagodas), tombs, and gardens, highlighting unique timber-frame construction and architectural achievements. Key texts like the *Yingzao Fashi* are introduced to understand traditional building principles and aesthetics.
This course explores the architectural history of ancient China, focusing on its unique wooden structural system and key building types such as palaces, temples, pagodas, tombs, and gardens. It highlights significant achievements from various dynasties, including grand capitals, religious complexes, and classical texts like the "Yingzao Fashi," illustrating China's advanced construction techniques and aesthetic traditions.
This course explores Chinese architectural history from the Yuan to Qing dynasties, focusing on palaces, religious structures, pagodas, tombs, and vernacular dwellings. It examines the unique timber-frame system, iconic examples like the Forbidden City and Temple of Heaven, and classical gardens. Key technical texts, such as the "Yingzao Fashi," are also introduced to illuminate traditional construction principles and aesthetics.
This course explores the architectural history of China, focusing on imperial cities, palaces, religious structures, pagodas, tombs, and classical gardens. It highlights traditional wooden and brick-stone construction techniques, key historical texts like the "Yingzao Fashi," and iconic examples such as the Forbidden City and the Temple of Heaven.
This course introduces fundamental concepts of reinforced concrete durability, focusing on the three-element analysis method. It aims to equip students with the ability to apply this analytical approach to both daily life and engineering practices, contributing to the enhancement of concrete structure longevity.
This self-paced course focuses on radiative heat transfer in participating media, such as gases and particles, crucial in high-temperature systems like boilers and aerospace vehicles. It centers on the Radiative Transfer Equation (RTE), covering its derivation, solution methods, and applications. The curriculum also addresses radiative properties and introduces advanced analytical techniques, including the Monte Carlo method and inverse problem solving.
This course systematically introduces fundamental principles, design concepts, and methods in automotive crash safety. It covers crash response analysis, occupant protection systems, structural design for various impact scenarios, and material behavior under impact. The curriculum addresses key safety evaluations and emerging technologies like electric vehicle battery safety, emphasizing engineering applications for regulatory compliance and injury reduction.
This course systematically introduces the fundamentals, design principles, and methods of automotive crash safety, covering core topics such as crash response analysis, occupant restraint systems, structural protection, and material behavior under impact. It addresses key safety standards and explores advanced technologies for vehicle and passenger protection.
This course on Systematic Product Design and Development (Spring 2019) teaches a structured approach to creating competitive products. It covers identifying market opportunities, understanding customer needs, generating product concepts, and managing development from design to manufacturing. Key topics include timing product launches, protecting intellectual property, and ensuring cost-effective, high-quality production.
This course comprehensively covers core data mining techniques, including data preprocessing, classification, clustering, regression, association, recommendation, ensemble learning, and evolutionary computation. It balances breadth, depth, and engagement, teaching key concepts and practical applications with a focus on useful knowledge and analytical thinking, rather than pure theory. Suitable for students and professionals interested in big data and data science.
This 2019 spring course, "Marketing: A Must-Have Course for Everyone," teaches essential marketing concepts and strategies for promoting products, brands, ideas, and oneself. It focuses on attracting customers without direct selling, offering practical problem-solving approaches. Led by Professor Zheng Yuhuang, it includes access to live discussions with entrepreneurs.
This graduate course "Financial Analysis and Decision-Making" introduces financial statements and frameworks to decode how businesses create value. It explores how financial data reflects strategy, operations, and industry dynamics. Learners develop financial thinking to apply insights to strategic positioning, performance evaluation, investment analysis, and risk assessment, enabling data-driven business decisions—no prior accounting knowledge required.
This McKinsey "Global Leadership" online course features six modules covering global trends, investment, technology, transformation, operations, and organization. Led by McKinsey's chairman and top CXOs, it uses real cases to develop forward-thinking vision and leadership skills for managing change, innovation, and crises in a global context.
This Tsinghua University credit course (32 hours, 2 credits) explores China's real estate development through its industrial chain and property types. It analyzes the sector's role in the national economy and challenges to sustainable growth. Developed by the Tsinghua Alumni Real Estate Association, it features exercises and a final exam for assessment.
This course examines institutional ethics in public affairs and moral dilemmas faced by public managers. Through case studies, classic texts, and dialogue, it analyzes ethical reasoning behind decisions and public values. It aims to develop participants' ethical awareness, logical thinking, and practical skills for public service, fostering reflection and discussion on diverse perspectives.
This course, offered at Tsinghua University since 2004, systematically explores public crisis characteristics, causes, and management. It focuses on governmental strategies, risk assessment, decision-making, crisis communication, and organizational coordination. Students develop skills to analyze, prevent, and respond to crises, enhancing both research and practical capabilities in public crisis management.
This self-paced Public Crisis Management course, offered since 2004, systematically explores the characteristics, causes, and mechanisms of public crises. It equips learners with skills in risk analysis, crisis decision-making, communication, and organizational coordination. The curriculum focuses on enhancing the capacity of public organizations to effectively prevent, analyze, and respond to various crises, promoting societal resilience.
This course explores social innovation and entrepreneurship within public management. It covers foundational theories, development stages, tools, and practical applications, aiming to broaden students' understanding of this emerging field. Students will learn new public management approaches and cultivate social entrepreneurial mindsets to address complex societal challenges and enhance human welfare.
This course explores the interplay between education and society, focusing on social mobility, systemic analysis of education, and globalization's impact. It covers topics like social inequality, gender equality, classroom dynamics, and educational reforms, using sociological theories to examine real-world issues and inform personal and professional educational strategies.
This self-paced Sociology of Education course explores the interplay between education and society. It covers social mobility, systemic analysis of education, and globalization's impact. Through ten lectures, topics include social inequality, gender equality, classroom dynamics, and educational reforms. Using data-driven theories, it examines how education shapes individuals and societies, helping learners develop informed perspectives and personal educational strategies.
This course introduces positive psychology, focusing on character strengths and virtues rooted in Chinese culture. It covers topics like happiness, optimism, positive emotions, and relationships, aiming to help learners apply these principles for a more fulfilling life.
This course, "Positive Psychology (Part 2): Self-Improvement," focuses on applying positive psychology principles within a Chinese cultural context. It covers topics like flow, motivation, values, self-concept, resilience, creativity, and well-being. The curriculum integrates modern research with traditional Chinese virtues and classics, aiming to equip learners with practical strategies for a more fulfilling and resilient life.
This course covers the fundamentals of IC design and methodology, focusing on both front-end and back-end processes. It introduces digital system architecture, RTL coding using VHDL/Verilog, logic synthesis, and layout planning. Key topics include simulation tools, synthesis concepts, and design verification techniques for integrated circuits.
This course focuses on practical English reading and writing skills through eight life themes, including learning, culture, and communication. It features thematic texts, reading strategies, writing workshops, interviews, and literary appreciation, all designed to enhance comprehension and expression in real-world contexts.
This self-paced course focuses on practical English reading and writing skills for daily life. Covering eight themes including study, culture, and communication, it features authentic texts, reading strategies, writing workshops with feedback, and literary appreciation. Led by instructors and Tsinghua students, the course enhances comprehension and expression through real-world scenarios.
This course enhances academic English proficiency across disciplines like psychology, engineering, and economics. It focuses on specialized vocabulary, text analysis, and cross-cultural communication, incorporating lectures, discussions, and writing workshops led by Tsinghua students and international instructors to improve effective communication in academic and daily contexts.
This introductory chemistry course builds upon high school foundations, exploring core theories like atomic structure, chemical bonding, thermodynamics, and kinetics. It emphasizes the connections between chemistry and real-world applications in industry, research, and daily life. The course aims to develop chemical thinking and problem-solving skills through lectures, assignments, and research-based projects.
This college-level introductory mechanics course covers core topics including kinematics, dynamics, momentum, energy, rigid bodies, vibrations, waves, and special relativity. Designed for advanced high school students with strong math and physics foundations, it employs concise video lectures and demonstrations to explain fundamental physical laws and problem-solving methods. The course requires basic calculus and vector knowledge and offers potential university credit through proctored exams.
This course introduces probability theory and mathematical statistics, covering fundamental concepts like random variables, probability distributions, expectation, variance, common distributions, limit theorems, parameter estimation, and hypothesis testing. It emphasizes mathematical methods for analyzing randomness and statistical patterns, aiming to develop analytical skills and a theoretical foundation for further studies.
This concise linear algebra course covers fundamental concepts including vectors, matrices, determinants, and systems of linear equations. Students will develop skills in matrix algebra, vector spaces, linear transformations, and diagonalization, enhancing analytical and problem-solving abilities in mathematical reasoning.
This introductory Calculus course covers core concepts including limits, derivatives, integrals, and their applications. Designed for advanced high school students, it provides systematic training in single-variable calculus, preparing learners for university-level mathematics and strengthening their analytical skills.
This preparatory course, "General Academic English," covers eight interdisciplinary units including culture, life sciences, and economics. It focuses on vocabulary, complex sentence analysis, and academic strategies taught by native speakers. Through discussions led by Tsinghua students, it aims to enhance cross-cultural awareness and communication skills for effective English use in academic and daily contexts. The course offers Tsinghua University credit certification upon passing online and offline exams.
This introductory linear algebra course covers core topics including linear equations, matrices, determinants, vector spaces, and matrix diagonalization. Designed for advanced high school students, it builds strong computational and analytical skills, equivalent to a college-level Linear Algebra C course. Successful completion offers potential university credit through China's CAP program.
This introductory probability and statistics course covers fundamental concepts including classical probability models, random variables, probability distributions, expectation, variance, common distributions, covariance, correlation, law of large numbers, central limit theorem, parameter estimation, and hypothesis testing. Designed for high school students with basic calculus, it emphasizes mathematical approaches to randomness, statistical reasoning, and practical applications, preparing students for university-level studies.
This pre-university chemistry course builds upon high school curriculum to introduce fundamental theories and real-world applications. It covers atomic structure, chemical bonds, thermodynamics, kinetics, and electrochemistry while emphasizing interdisciplinary connections. The course enhances problem-solving skills through lectures, assignments, and research projects, with teaching assistant support available. Successful online completion allows participants to pursue credit-bearing offline exams recognized by participating universities.
This introductory General Biology course provides a foundational overview of life sciences, covering core principles at molecular, cellular, and organismal levels. It explores cell biology, molecular genetics, plant and animal structure/function, and key biological processes. The course aims to build a comprehensive knowledge framework, preparing students for advanced biology studies through concise video lectures and assessments.
This college-level introductory electromagnetism course for advanced high school students covers core topics including electrostatic fields, conductors, electric currents, magnetism, electromagnetic induction, and Maxwell's equations. Through concise video lectures and demonstrations, it teaches fundamental physical laws and problem-solving methods, requiring basic calculus and vector knowledge.
This online course introduces Grasshopper for parametric design, complementing Tsinghua University's CAAD internship. It covers core concepts like algorithmic logic, data structures, Nurbs/Mesh modeling, and Kangaroo physics simulation. Using visual programming, students learn to generate geometric forms rationally, enhancing adaptability in architectural, urban, and landscape design. Ideal for designers seeking efficient, scalable tools.
This course introduces fundamental theories of electricity markets, covering economic principles, mid-to-long-term and spot market mechanisms, ancillary services, financial markets, regulatory methods, bidding optimization, and technical support systems. It analyzes real-world cases like California and PJM markets, while discussing China's market development and unique characteristics.
This course focuses on practical valuation techniques for investments like securities and M&A. It covers forecasting financial statements, free cash flow, EVA, and multiples valuation, emphasizing application over theory. Prerequisites include basic accounting and financial statement analysis skills.
This micro-course series provides university instructors, particularly young faculty at Tsinghua, with essential knowledge on curriculum and teaching. It covers course planning, syllabus design, teaching methods, assignment strategies, and assessment techniques. The goal is to equip educators with practical, operational skills to enhance teaching effectiveness and support student-centered learning, aligning with broader educational reform trends.
This course offers a guided introduction to the philosophy of Zhuangzi, focusing on the seven core chapters of the "Inner Chapters." It explores key philosophical themes including his views on life, the world, knowledge, society, morality, life and death, and governance. The approach is primarily philosophical, examining the coherent system and profound wisdom within these foundational texts.
This course, recognized by China's Ministry of Education, equips educators to design, produce, and operate effective MOOCs. As an advanced guide to online teaching, it covers key aspects from course planning to video production and platform management, preparing instructors to excel in digital education.
This micro-course introduces ARM microcontroller and embedded system basics for the "National Intelligent Vehicle Competition." It covers fundamental development methods using 32-bit ARM Cortex-M chips, enabling beginners to quickly start projects and participate in tech competitions.
This course features recorded thesis defenses from Tsinghua University's 2014 graduate students across disciplines like economics, engineering, and sciences. It aims to share academic research, enhance education quality, and provide a platform for scholarly exchange by making these defense videos publicly accessible.
This course features recorded thesis defenses from Tsinghua University's 2015 doctoral and master's graduates across various disciplines. Shared as a MOOC, it aims to promote academic exchange and provide valuable research insights by showcasing exemplary defense presentations, continuing a public video initiative launched in 2014.
This course features recorded thesis defense sessions from Tsinghua University's 2015 graduate students. It aims to promote academic exchange and enhance research training quality by sharing representative doctoral and master's presentations. These videos provide insights into formal academic evaluation and diverse research topics across disciplines.
This course features recorded thesis defenses from Tsinghua University graduate students. It aims to showcase the academic review process, foster scholarly exchange, and enhance educational quality. Presented as a MOOC, these videos offer public access to diverse disciplinary defenses for learning and inspiration.
This course, "Winning in the Mobile Internet Era: A Business Model Course for Entrepreneurs (Spring 2019)," teaches entrepreneurs and innovators to identify opportunities and develop successful business models in the mobile internet age. Led by instructor Shen Tuo, it focuses on strategic foresight, creating breakthrough products, and securing growth from startup to scale.
This course explores innovative applications of materials across ten key fields, including semiconductors, renewable energy, and environmental protection. It introduces over 100 essential concepts in an accessible, engaging manner, focusing on current advancements and practical uses rather than deep theoretical foundations. Designed for students and professionals in science and engineering, it provides a broad, up-to-date overview of modern materials science.
This course, "Information Literacy: Essential for Academic Research," provides foundational skills for effective scholarly inquiry. It covers literature search basics, common retrieval pitfalls, practical search techniques, and use of reference tools. Participants also learn to leverage online resources, understand academic norms, and employ digital tools for knowledge management, enhancing research efficiency across disciplines.
This course develops essential information literacy skills for academic research. It covers literature search fundamentals, common retrieval pitfalls, practical search techniques, and data retrieval methods. Participants also learn to utilize online resources, understand academic norms, and employ knowledge management tools to enhance research efficiency across disciplines.
This course introduces fundamental concepts of big data systems, covering efficient data storage, processing, and analysis. It explores distributed system design principles, frameworks for scaling storage and computation, and uses real-world case studies to demonstrate practical applications and performance analysis.
This advanced chemical thermodynamics course derives classical thermodynamic laws from four fundamental postulates. It covers core principles including the first and second laws, equilibrium, stability, and property calculations for pure substances and mixtures. The course applies these concepts to solve practical engineering problems in chemical, materials, and biological systems, focusing on phase and chemical equilibrium.
This Microeconomics (Spring 2019) course introduces core principles including supply, demand, and price formation. It develops foundational economic thinking and market analysis skills, covering topics like government intervention. Assessment includes 16 weekly quizzes (80%) and a final exam (20%). Completion with a passing score earns a Tsinghua University certificate.
This course features renowned Tsinghua scholars from humanities and social sciences. Students attend lectures, watch academic dialogues, and engage in guided readings of classic works. Through discussions and assignments, they explore key theories and discoveries across seven units, each led by a distinguished expert.
This course features renowned Tsinghua scholars from humanities and social sciences, exploring classic theories and contemporary insights. Students engage with lectures, academic dialogues, and guided readings of masterworks. Structured into seven units, each includes expert talks, interviews, reading sessions, and discussions led by doctoral assistants.
This course features recorded thesis defense sessions from Tsinghua University graduate students in 2016. It showcases representative doctoral and master's degree presentations across various disciplines, shared as MOOCs to promote academic exchange and enhance research quality. The videos offer insights into formal defense procedures and scholarly discussions.
This course features recorded thesis defenses from Tsinghua University's 2017 master's and doctoral students across various disciplines. Shared as a MOOC, it aims to provide academic exchange and insight into the thesis defense process, enhancing research quality and offering valuable learning resources to a broad audience.
This introductory Mandarin course combines language basics (taught in English) with instructional design principles (in Chinese). Following a learner's perspective, it addresses fundamental teaching challenges like pronunciation and grammar distinctions. Designed for beginners and aspiring teachers, it also offers English language practice. The course is developed by Tsinghua University professors and available on edX.
This course examines high-tech modern warfare, analyzing its origins, characteristics, and development trends through recent case studies. It explores the impact of technological warfare on military strategy, global dynamics, and national defense, with a focus on China's security challenges and military advancements. The course aims to broaden strategic thinking and analytical skills regarding contemporary military conflicts.
This course explores laser fundamentals, contrasting laser coherence with thermal light. It covers single longitudinal mode selection in resonators via light-matter interactions, laser rate equations, and active energy levels. Students learn key laser radiation properties for material processing, propagation dynamics, and industrial applications in laser machining and measurement.
This self-paced course covers fundamentals of control engineering, focusing on modeling, time-domain and frequency-domain analysis, stability, error assessment, and controller design for closed-loop systems. It provides a solid foundation for mechanical engineering undergraduates.
CS 169.2x, the second part of UC Berkeley's SaaS course, teaches advanced SaaS development. Students build complex applications using relational models and JavaScript, learn performance monitoring and data protection for deployed apps, and apply Agile techniques to refactor legacy code. The course includes Rails design patterns, team management, and hands-on programming assignments.
This self-paced course introduces computer graphics fundamentals. Over 8 weeks, students learn to create images of 3D scenes using real-time and offline ray tracing. It covers core topics like mathematical foundations, transformations, OpenGL, lighting, and ray tracing through four programming assignments. Passing requires achieving at least 50% of the total grade.
This introductory English writing course for language learners focuses on essay writing, grammar application, and self-editing. Over 15 weeks, it covers basic grammar, sentence and paragraph structure, introductions and conclusions, and strategies for longer texts. Students engage with readings, videos, and a digital workbook, participate in peer reviews, and complete a final essay.
This 30-hour course for professional masters covers embedded systems fundamentals, processors, operating systems, software platforms, and Linux driver development. It combines 16 hours of theory with 14 hours of lab work. Over five semesters, about 80 students per term learn core concepts and practical platform usage, preparing them for embedded systems engineering roles.
This course covers the principles and development of database systems, focusing on core technologies for data management and application systems. Students will learn database design, programming, and development skills to build practical database applications and enhance innovation capabilities.
This course provides university students with an education on national security, guided by Xi Jinping's holistic approach to national security. It covers national security strategy, management, and legal frameworks, using real-world case studies to illustrate key concepts. The course is taught by an experienced team, including professors from the acclaimed "Decoding National Security" program. Assessment combines video lectures, assignments, and a final exam.
This introductory course on biomedical imaging covers modern techniques, their underlying scientific principles, and key applications ranging from neurological disorders to cancer. It addresses common misconceptions while offering modules tailored for both the general public and professionals in health, engineering, and IT fields.
This course explores the effectiveness of legal and judicial systems from a psychological perspective. Students engage with a fictional case to learn about legal psychology and common misconceptions in criminal justice.
This self-paced course explores tropical coastline ecosystems, their vital species, and threats like overfishing, pollution, and climate change. Led by experts, it offers skills for conservation and includes a virtual ecology project. Developed by the University of Queensland's Heron Island Research Station.
This course examines the science of everyday thinking, exploring why people believe unusual claims and how to improve decision-making. It covers cognitive biases, evidence evaluation, and psychological shortcuts through topics like medical diagnoses and supernatural phenomena. Featuring insights from experts like Daniel Kahneman, it provides tools for critical, logical analysis over automatic thinking.
This course explores the science of everyday thinking, examining why people believe unusual claims and how to improve decision-making. It covers topics like cognitive biases, evidence evaluation, and psychological shortcuts, featuring insights from experts like Daniel Kahneman. Students learn tools for critical, logical analysis over automatic thinking.
This self-paced "Network Technology and Applications" course covers TCP/IP architecture, core networking concepts, and protocols using Cisco Packet Tracer for hands-on simulation. It prepares students for China's Computer Rank Exam Level 3 (Network Technology) and CCNA certification, focusing on designing, configuring, and troubleshooting networks, including LANs, Internet access, and basic security.
This course explores internet architecture through hands-on Linux-based analysis, covering TCP/IP protocols, routing, ARP, and Layer 2 switching. Using MenuOS for code tracing, it examines DNS naming, IP networking, and data exchange processes to reveal the design philosophy and evolution of network systems.
This "Web Security Practice" course introduces foundational web security concepts for beginners. It covers common vulnerabilities like XSS, CSRF, SQL injection, and DoS attacks, alongside defense techniques. Through hands-on implementation on a course website, students gain practical programming experience and a deep understanding of secure web application development principles.
This course introduces multivariable calculus, covering limits, derivatives, differentials, and integrals of functions of several variables. It emphasizes comparing and contrasting with single-variable calculus, understanding concepts through geometric and physical contexts, and applying knowledge to geometry and physics for practical learning.
This course explores internet architecture through practical Linux-based examples, covering network commands, Socket programming, TCP/IP protocols, routing, ARP, and Layer 2 switching. Using MenuOS for code analysis, it explains web browsing processes across DNS naming, IP networking, and data link layers. The course also examines historical evolution, design philosophy, and future network trends.
This course covers modern product design principles and development processes. It focuses on cultivating systematic thinking, innovation capabilities, and product evaluation methods. Students will learn core approaches to product development and value assessment.
This course systematically introduces entrepreneurship fundamentals, covering idea generation, business planning, startup establishment, financing, and growth management. It aims to develop entrepreneurial mindset, problem-solving skills, and self-management capabilities, preparing learners to act as innovators whether launching ventures or driving change within organizations.
This course introduces core technologies for large-scale internet data analysis. It covers big data platforms like Hadoop and Spark, NoSQL databases, and the MapReduce model, along with classic data mining algorithms. Students will explore information retrieval and recommendation systems, using tools such as Lucene and Mahout to build practical applications like search engines and recommendation systems.
This course on Internet-Scale Data Analysis Technologies introduces core big data tools like Hadoop, Spark, NoSQL, and MapReduce. It covers key data mining algorithms and explores principles of information retrieval and recommendation systems. Using examples and open-source tools like Lucene and Mahout, students learn to extract insights from massive datasets and build practical applications such as search engines and recommendation systems.
This course explores the principles of networks, groups, and markets in an interconnected world. It integrates concepts from economics, sociology, computer science, and applied mathematics to analyze real-world phenomena like social networks, traffic patterns, and electoral systems. Students learn to apply computational thinking to understand and solve complex socio-economic problems.
This course explores the interconnectedness of modern society through networks like the web and social media. It applies interdisciplinary tools from economics, sociology, computer science, and applied mathematics to analyze real-world phenomena, such as social influence, traffic patterns, and electoral systems. The goal is to cultivate computational thinking for understanding and solving complex socio-economic problems in a highly connected world.
This course explores the fundamental structures and mechanisms of design through comparative case studies. It equips learners with a systematic framework to analyze design elements, derive principles, and develop diverse research and practice strategies. Accessible without prior specialized knowledge, it offers methodological insights applicable across humanities disciplines.
This introductory nutrition course, led by Professor Sander Kersten from Wageningen University, focuses on overnutrition and the relationship between diet and health. It covers the chemistry, absorption, storage, and metabolism of macronutrients—fats, carbohydrates, and proteins—and their impact on health. The course also explores energy balance, weight regulation, obesity, and fundamental nutrition research methods. Learners will gain tools to critically evaluate nutrition information. No prior knowledge is required.
This course provides an overview of human evolution, covering key developments from our last common ancestor with apes to modern humans. It examines fossil records, DNA studies, and archaeological findings to explore major evolutionary changes, including the divergence from apes, Australopithecus, the genus Homo, and recent shifts linked to agriculture. Students will learn about research methods and major theories in paleoanthropology.
This course examines Alexander the Great's life, leadership, and epic conquests, exploring his impact on warfare, human psychology, and East-West relations. It addresses his controversial legacy and the historical perspectives on his role in shaping ancient multicultural empires and religious ideologies.
This course explores the historical novel "Tongwan City," focusing on the rise and mysterious disappearance of the Xiongnu people's capital and the cultural contributions of translator Kumarajiva. It covers the history of the Xiongnu, their final king Helian Bobo, and Kumarajiva's journey in spreading Buddhist scriptures, blending historical analysis with literary themes.
This graduate-level course on Compiler Technology (Spring 2019) provides a comprehensive understanding of the compilation process for high-level programming languages. It covers fundamental principles of program translation, combining theory and practice to develop students' abstract thinking and problem-solving skills in system software development. The course includes video lectures, assignments, quizzes, discussions, and a final exam for assessment.
This graduate-level course in Compiler Technology provides a comprehensive understanding of the compilation process and principles for high-level programming languages. It focuses on theoretical foundations and practical skills for developing system translation software, enhancing problem-solving and abstract thinking abilities. Assessment includes chapter quizzes and a final exam.
This introductory Python course teaches interactive programming through game development. Students learn computational thinking by designing, coding, and testing programs. It develops problem-solving skills using formal language and systematic approaches. No prior programming experience is required.
This introductory chemistry course covers fundamental concepts including atomic structure, chemical bonding, thermodynamics, chemical equilibrium, reaction rates, solution chemistry, and electrochemistry. Designed for non-chemistry STEM majors, it emphasizes foundational principles, systematic knowledge, and the development of scientific problem-solving skills through 48 hours of lectures and labs.
This course examines contemporary national defense issues, focusing on China's evolving security landscape beyond traditional borders. It aims to cultivate students' overall national security perspective, strategic thinking, and rational analysis of complex global affairs, fostering a sense of responsibility to safeguard national interests.
Periodontology is a specialized dental field focusing on periodontal tissues' structure, physiology, and diseases. This course covers the etiology, diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of periodontal diseases, which affect tooth-supporting structures and are a leading cause of tooth loss in adults. It also explores links between periodontal and systemic health.
This course provides a comprehensive overview of respiratory diseases, covering their epidemiology, etiology, diagnosis, treatment, and prevention. It emphasizes clinical reasoning, medical humanities, and public health responsibilities like smoking cessation and chronic disease management. Utilizing multimedia resources, it systematically explores common conditions to train skilled respiratory specialists.
This course offers a guided introduction to classic Chinese philosophical texts, covering key works from Confucianism, Daoism, Buddhism, and Neo-Confucianism. It explores foundational ideas from texts like the *Analects*, *Dao De Jing*, and *Zhuangzi*, providing a comprehensive overview of traditional Chinese thought. The course aims to foster a broad, integrated understanding of these philosophical traditions.
This course provides an introductory guide to classic Chinese philosophical works, covering key texts from Confucianism, Daoism, Buddhism, and Neo-Confucianism. It explores major thinkers like Confucius, Laozi, Zhuangzi, and Wang Yangming, offering a comprehensive overview of traditional Chinese philosophy. The course aims to broaden perspectives and deepen understanding of these foundational ideas.
This concise organic chemistry preparatory course covers fundamental concepts including compound structures, nomenclature, properties, functional group transformations, and stereochemistry. It introduces key reaction mechanisms and applications, equipping students with essential theoretical knowledge and practical skills. Designed for first- and second-year undergraduates, the course offers Xi'an Jiaotong University credit certification upon completion.
This course introduces the fundamentals of microcomputer principles and interface technology, covering topics such as microprocessor architecture, assembly language programming, memory and I/O interface design, and analog/digital conversion. It equips learners with essential skills for designing basic computer-based control systems and provides a foundation for further studies in microcontroller and embedded systems development.
This course covers procurement planning, bidding processes, contract formulation, and dispute resolution in project management. It emphasizes practical application through real-world cases, teaching both domestic and international standards to enhance theoretical knowledge and operational skills in procurement and contract management.
This self-paced Medical Ethics course explores the intersection of medicine and ethics, emphasizing the integration of moral character and clinical skill for physicians. It examines medical practices through an ethical lens, highlighting the profession's humanitarian mission to protect life and promote health, thereby underscoring the essential humanistic nature of medicine.
This course provides comprehensive training in pediatric nursing, covering child health, nutrition, growth, disease prevention, and care skills. It combines theoretical instruction with practical application to equip students with essential knowledge and competencies in pediatric healthcare.
This course explores the secrets of cross-cultural communication in educational settings. It covers key aspects like verbal and nonverbal exchanges, interpersonal interactions, and common challenges. Through five modules, students learn foundational theories, identify issues, analyze cultural causes, and develop strategies to enhance communication effectiveness across cultures.
This course explores human anatomy through everyday phenomena, covering 11 systems including digestion, respiration, circulation, and neurology. It connects structural knowledge with practical health insights, explaining common diseases and preventive care for real-life application.
This introductory computer course for non-majors covers essential computer fundamentals, including basic concepts, operating systems, networking, Office software applications, and multimedia technology. It emphasizes foundational knowledge and practical information literacy skills for academic and lifelong use.
This course focuses on core marketing skills, centered on consumer needs. It covers marketing concepts, market research, and analysis of the digital marketing environment and business strategies. Students learn to develop and apply product, pricing, promotion, and distribution strategies for the internet era, aiming for effective marketing management and multi-stakeholder value creation.
This online course on Plant Tissue Culture Technology features 40 videos across four modules. It covers fundamental principles, essential techniques, rapid propagation, and virus-free technology, with demonstrations of key practical operations. Designed to guide vocational students and seedling producers in mastering plant tissue culture methods.
This course focuses on oral health awareness, highlighting how neglecting symptoms like bleeding gums can lead to tooth loss and systemic diseases. It emphasizes prevention through personal care and professional check-ups, aiming for lifelong dental wellness.
This foundational engineering drawing course introduces orthographic projection principles, covering geometric element representation, basic solid intersections, and component expression methods. It develops spatial visualization, drafting, and technical drawing interpretation skills essential for measurement, electrical, automation, and environmental engineering disciplines.
This concise linear algebra course covers essential topics including matrices, vectors, linear equations, and transformations. It provides foundational mathematical tools for analyzing multi-variable relationships, with applications across engineering, computer science, and natural sciences. Students develop analytical problem-solving skills through rigorous theoretical frameworks.
"Principles of Management" (Spring 2019) is a foundational course covering core management theories, functions, and practices. It systematically explores key topics including planning, organizing, leading, and controlling. The course emphasizes practical application through case studies, enterprise interactions, and analytical exercises, aiming to develop students' managerial thinking and problem-solving skills while fostering professional ethics and values.
This Business Etiquette course, a 2019 provincial-level online offering, provides practical training in professional conduct. It combines instructional lectures with extensive video demonstrations and exercises across 34 key topics. Designed for university students, the course has received consistently high ratings over two years of multi-platform delivery.
This self-paced Business Etiquette course, a top-rated online program in Zhejiang, offers practical training through 34 instructional videos and exercises. It combines expert instruction with hands-on demonstrations to teach professional conduct effectively. Designed for university students, it has received high praise over two years of multi-platform delivery.
This self-paced Environmental Engineering CAD course teaches core design principles and AutoCAD skills for environmental projects. It covers site planning, process flow diagrams, facility layout, and piping design through theoretical lessons and practical exercises. Students learn to create professional engineering drawings, preparing them for careers in environmental management and design.
This course provides a systematic introduction to valuing internet companies, covering core principles, standard valuation methods, and case studies including unicorn firms. It connects valuation practices with China's economic context and capital markets, requiring foundational knowledge in economics, finance, or accounting. The course aims to build professional expertise in assessing both tangible and intangible assets of enterprises.
"Case-Based Law" explores China's legal system through real-life cases, covering constitutional, civil, criminal, and economic law. It connects legal theory with practical life challenges, enhancing legal awareness and civic responsibility. The course aims to foster law comprehension, compliance, and advocacy, contributing to the rule of law in China.
This course explores economic geography, focusing on the dynamic relationship between business activities and geographical environments. It examines how spatial changes in modern industrial societies influence corporate success and decline. Emphasizing fundamental questions like "where?" and "why?", it requires no advanced prerequisites.
This "Fundamentals of Entrepreneurship" course introduces core entrepreneurial concepts and practical skills through seven interconnected modules. It combines theoretical education with hands-on training and real-world practice, aiming to develop students' entrepreneurial mindset, abilities, and foundational skills. The course emphasizes problem-solving in the entrepreneurial process and adapts teaching methods to suit different learners.
This course explores core principles of organizational behavior, focusing on effectively managing and motivating employees to build high-performance teams. Through clear logic and practical case studies, it decodes the underlying factors driving employee behavior in managerial contexts.
This course explores organizational behavior, focusing on effective employee management. It covers motivation, behavior control, and building high-performance teams. Using clear logic and real-world cases, it decodes employee actions in managerial contexts to enhance leadership skills.
This course explores organizational behavior, focusing on effectively managing and motivating employees to build high-performance teams. Through clear logic and real-world cases, it decodes the underlying factors driving employee actions in managerial contexts, equipping learners with essential skills for successful leadership.
This course explores modern internal control and risk management as value-creating activities. It focuses on integrating strategic goals, governance, and corporate culture into comprehensive risk frameworks. Key topics include risk analysis, control implementation, and process improvement to enhance overall organizational management and performance.
This self-paced course covers internal control and risk management, focusing on the shift from traditional loss prevention to value-driven comprehensive risk management. It explores integrating strategic goals, governance, and corporate culture into control systems through risk analysis, mitigation, and process improvements to enhance overall management effectiveness.
This course explores the intersection of the imperial examination system and Tang poetry, highlighting their cultural significance. It examines how exams influenced poetic themes, forms, and social mobility, covering topics like examination poems and poets' experiences. The course connects historical insights with modern relevance through structured units and assessed assignments.
This course explores the application of information technology in education. It focuses on hands-on, task-driven learning in real-world scenarios to help students understand, master, and utilize IT tools. The goal is to transform learning concepts, enhance information literacy, and equip learners with essential 21st-century digital skills.
This course offers a comprehensive guide to digital photography, covering both fundamental techniques and advanced skills. Through a blend of video lectures, hands-on practice, and photo analysis, it enhances students' technical abilities and aesthetic appreciation. Practical tips are taught within various themes and scenarios, fostering artistic expression and a positive outlook on life.
This course introduces the systematic study of marketing activities, focusing on how market-driven exchanges fulfill human needs and desires. It covers core principles and scientific methods to effectively facilitate transactions between buyers and sellers, emphasizing practical applications in both production and consumption contexts.
This course, "Information Literacy in the Internet+ Era: Learning and Life (Spring 2019)," focuses on developing comprehensive information literacy skills. It covers core topics including information retrieval, evaluation, ethics, and management, alongside practical applications like search engines, academic patent searches, and information security. Designed as an online course, it aims to enhance students' ability to solve problems independently using information in the digital age.
This graduate-level course "Catalyst Design and Preparation" covers core principles and methods for designing and fabricating catalysts, including precipitation, sol-gel, impregnation, and hydrothermal techniques. It focuses on industrial catalysts like oxides, supported catalysts, and zeolites, equipping students with essential knowledge for careers in petrochemicals, energy, environmental engineering, and applied chemistry.
This practical knot-tying course, with a maritime focus, teaches fundamental knot techniques for daily use and artistic expression. It enhances hands-on skills and maritime culture awareness for all students, while providing essential seamanship training for future航海 professionals to ensure vessel safety.
This course, "Marine Engine Automation (Autonomous Mode)", is a core professional course for marine engineering students. It focuses on autonomous innovation in automation equipment, integrated systems, and software simulation. With over 50 years of history, it is a national-level精品course, recognized for leading teaching reforms and modernizing experimental setups in the field.
This course provides a comprehensive introduction to navigation, covering five key areas: an overview of navigation's concepts and significance; crew culture, contributions, and duties; ship development, types, structure, and essential equipment; fundamental navigation knowledge, voyage planning, positioning, and watchkeeping; and maritime safety conventions like SOLAS and pollution prevention regulations.
This self-paced course explores blended learning principles and practical strategies for effectively integrating online educational technology into traditional classrooms. It covers design approaches, implementation challenges, and real-world examples using edX content to enhance student engagement and learning outcomes.
Pathophysiology explores disease causes, mechanisms, and progression by examining functional and metabolic changes in the body. It covers general disease principles, basic pathological processes, and system-specific disorders, serving as a bridge between basic and clinical medicine to inform disease prevention and treatment.
Pharmaceutics is a comprehensive applied science focusing on the design, development, production, and rational use of drug dosage forms. Its core objective is to formulate safe, effective, stable, and convenient pharmaceutical preparations that meet quality standards for clinical application in disease prevention, treatment, and diagnosis.
Medicinal Chemistry is a core interdisciplinary course integrating chemistry, life sciences, and computer applications. It builds upon foundational knowledge in chemistry, medicine, and biology to explore drug design, development, and mechanisms. The course emphasizes both classical principles and modern innovations, preparing students for roles in pharmaceutical research and development through updated content and teaching methods.
This course, "The Art of Teaching," introduces pedagogical artistry using the textbook "Teaching Art Theory." Designed for education majors, it blends theory with practice to enhance teaching skills. Building on psychology and education foundations, it helps students master teaching methods and develop personal instructional styles. The teaching team combines academic expertise with practical school experience.
This course covers structured cabling systems (PDS) for intelligent buildings, integrating voice, data, and multimedia transmission via twisted pair or fiber optics. Students learn design, installation, testing, and troubleshooting, gaining essential skills for network infrastructure implementation and understanding current technological trends.
This professional course focuses on construction materials, covering their composition, properties, and applications. It teaches students to analyze material performance under various conditions and make appropriate selections. Designed for engineering and architecture majors, the course emphasizes practical skills in material evaluation, quality assessment, and industry standards.
This course explores the evolution of automotive technology, covering key stages from early human-powered and animal-drawn vehicles to steam engines, internal combustion engines, and modern electric vehicles. It explains the historical development, structural principles, and technological innovations in transportation, using detailed case studies and diverse teaching methods to make the content accessible and engaging.
This course covers the fundamentals of optics, including geometric optics, wave optics, and quantum optics. It integrates scientific history and humanistic perspectives to explore light's nature, covering topics such as interference, diffraction, polarization, and wave-particle duality. Designed for both beginners and advanced learners, it emphasizes conceptual understanding over exam-focused learning.
This course explores the Xixia (Western Xia) dynasty, a multi-ethnic regime founded by the Tangut people. It highlights its significant cultural and historical achievements, including early movable-type printing and unique contributions to Chinese literature and Confucian tradition. Led by expert scholars, the course provides a professional academic interpretation of this distinctive civilization.
This course explores the Xixia (Western Xia) dynasty, a multi-ethnic regime founded by the Tangut people. It highlights its significant cultural achievements, including early movable-type printing and unique Buddhist texts. Led by Professor Du Jianlu, the program delves into its political history and societal contributions, offering a comprehensive academic overview of this distinctive civilization.
This introductory course offers a clear and comprehensive guide to wine for beginners. It covers fundamental topics including wine history, grape varieties, and vineyard terroir. Through practical demonstrations, students learn tasting techniques, food pairing, etiquette, and winery operations. The goal is to provide essential knowledge and practical skills to help learners understand and appreciate wine.
This course explores human genetics through topics like hereditary diseases, physical traits, gender determination, and genetic engineering. It systematically covers genetic principles from cellular to molecular levels, integrating foundational knowledge with practical applications related to human health and traits.
This foundational course for non-electrical engineering majors covers essential theories and practical skills in electrical and electronic technology. It focuses on core principles, applications, and developing proficiency with modern tools through quality learning resources.
This course provides an introduction to Tibetan linguistics and writing systems. It traces the historical development of Tibetan script, established in the 7th century, and explains its structure, including alphabet grouping, arrangement, and writing rules. The curriculum covers the evolution of Tibetan characters and offers foundational knowledge in Tibetan philology, making it accessible to students and enthusiasts of Tibetan language and culture.
This course introduces Tibetan linguistics, focusing on the evolution and structure of the Tibetan script from the 7th century. It covers historical development, alphabet organization, grammar, and writing systems. Designed for students and enthusiasts, it offers expert instruction with clear bilingual explanations for effective learning.
This course provides a comprehensive introduction to online education from both theoretical and practical perspectives. It explores the rationale, current status in higher education, and future trends of e-learning. Featuring insights from leading university professors, it combines macro-level analysis with real-world teaching case studies to offer a holistic view of the digital classroom.
This course focuses on health management for common diseases, covering assessment, diagnosis, and treatment of conditions like thyroid disorders, cirrhosis, depression, and asthma. It emphasizes early prevention and effective strategies to control illnesses, aiming to enhance participants' health literacy and improve quality of life through practical education.
This course explores the integration of logical thinking and writing. It covers fundamental logic principles, reasoning techniques, and their application in structured writing. Students learn to analyze arguments, construct coherent essays, and enhance critical thinking skills for effective communication and problem-solving.
This course explores blended learning, integrating online self-study with in-person teaching to enhance student engagement and educational outcomes. It focuses on designing effective online and offline components, featuring insights from Tsinghua University instructors who share practical strategies for implementing learner-centered, personalized teaching reforms.